Russian President Vladimir Putin signed a law on the introduction of administrative responsibility for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in procurement for state and municipal needs.
This law is designed to solve the very acute problem of non-fulfillment of its obligations by customers in the implementation of public and municipal procurement.
Two years ago, the situation when entrepreneurs could not receive payment under already executed state and municipal contracts was widespread.
At the same time, the President of Russia instructed the Prosecutor General’s Office of the Russian Federation to take the problem under special control.
Because the businessmen themselves could not cope with unscrupulous customers who concluded unfunded contracts, tried in every way to evade the assumed payment obligations and included illegal conditions in the contracts.
The problem was systemic in the country as a whole.
Since 2015, in the interests of protecting the rights of entrepreneurs to receive payment on public orders, the prosecutor's office has filed 9.7 thousand submissions, according to the results of their consideration, 4.5 thousand officials have been brought to disciplinary responsibility, 533 to administrative, 75 materials have been submitted to the investigative bodies for organizing procedural inspections, 46 of them have been initiated criminal cases.
As a result, the debt to entrepreneurs in the amount of more than 66 billion rubles was repaid.
Moreover, these huge amounts were not accumulated as a result of non-payment of multibillion-dollar contracts.
The fabulous debts resulted in numerous, systematic delays in the payment of services to entrepreneurs for much more modest amounts.
Here is a typical case.
The head of a small company won a tender for the provision of social transportation services for several million rubles.
The man invested all his working capital, fully fulfilled his obligations, but did not receive the money on time.
The result is a growing financial coma from debts on salaries, taxes, loans, which would have led to bankruptcy if the entrepreneur had not sought help from the prosecutor’s office.
Now in some regions, the problem has been eliminated as much as possible.
Nevertheless, as of the first half of 2017, the total amount of debt under state and municipal contracts, identified by prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, amounted to about 27.4 billion rubles.
In regions where debt ratios continue to reach critical levels, the prosecutor’s office operates under manual crisis management.
The Attorney-General personally conducts field meetings with representatives of the local authorities, at which all violations uncovered by prosecutors are examined in detail and measures are taken to eliminate them immediately.
Such operational meetings have already been held this year in Yaroslavl and Yekaterinburg.
The implementation of the Federal Law No. 189-FZ "On Amendments to the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences in terms of establishing administrative responsibility of the officials of the customer for violation of the term and procedure for payment of goods (works, services) in procurement to meet state and municipal needs" will be able to qualitatively improve the payment discipline of public customers, which was signed by the President of Russia last week.
The draft law was developed by the Ministry of Economic Development of Russia on the initiative of the Prosecutor General’s Office.
The new law will supplement the Code of the Russian Federation on Administrative Offences with an article that provides for a fine of 30 thousand to 50 thousand rubles for violation by an official of the customer of the term and procedure for payment for goods, works and services in state and municipal procurement.
And if the official has already been subjected to administrative punishment for a similar offense, then he will be disqualified for a period of one to two years.
All prosecutors of the constituent entities of the Russian Federation have already been instructed to ensure the application of these legislative novelties in practice.
Civil Rights Group Announces Warning of Movement in Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri because of the state’s discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group’s statement reads: “The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People’s Travel Warning, valid until August 28, 2017, urges African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to be especially attentive and extra cautious when traveling around the state in connection with a number of questionable racist incidents that have recently occurred here and throughout the state.”
According to the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, the movement warning was prompted by a recent Missouri law that made it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the disproportionately frequent targeting of minority groups by state law enforcement agencies.
“You have people who are subject to human rights violations.
They are stopped on the roads because of their skin color, beaten and killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri National Association for the Advancement of Colored People, told the Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We hear complaints more often than ever before.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization against the US state.
The group cited incidents such as the racial humiliation of black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tori Sanders, a 28-year-old black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under suspicious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while on a state trip, and Missouri state police arrested him without charge of the crime.
The warning also mentions a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office, according to which black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped on the road than white drivers.
“The purpose of the warning is for people to be aware of the situation and to warn their relatives and friends and colleagues about what might happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared one way or another, whether they take the money with them for bail or tell relatives that they are traveling around the state.”
According to the latest data from the FBI’s hate crime reporting program, Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, making the state the 16th-highest number of hate crimes in the state.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to bring a case against a legal entity for housing or labor discrimination.
Earlier, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) issued warnings for travelers to Texas and Arizona after those states passed new immigration control laws that ordered local law enforcement agencies to arrest people for violating immigration laws, which the ACLU said was meant to increase the number of racially-based checks.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department in relation to other countries, but more recently public organizations have resorted to this measure in response to certain laws and trends within the United States.
