He received ten blows with a wooden stick on his buttocks and spent a week in prison.
Corporal punishment is not uncommon.
How Singapore combines the highest standard of living and incredibly harsh laws, the columnist “AIF” understood on the spot.
No one here thinks of abolishing the death penalty,” lawyer Victor Lee Hong explains.
And the government for a long time does not care about the opinion of both the European Union and the United States on this issue.
If a person carries a large consignment of drugs or sells them - he is put on a gallows.
In 2002, a 22-year-old Australian national was detained at Changi airport, carrying 400 grams of cocaine.
In his defense, the Australian Prime Minister, threatening sanctions, international human rights defenders and even the Pope.
