After that, drug couriers carefully travel around our country.
The fact is that in Singapore it is stipulated that the laws must comply with ALL in a row, and not only the modest and poor people.
It doesn’t matter if you are a millionaire, a deputy prime minister, a well-known artist or a resident of the European Union.
There's only one option: If you get a pound of cocaine, you'll be hanged.
When you walk around Singapore and everywhere you meet signs with a bunch of warnings, by a simple miracle you give - how many prohibitions in this city-state!
For example, chewing gum is sold only in pharmacies, and you can buy it strictly according to the doctor's prescription (!)
The tourist on arrival, the gum will not be taken away, but it is worth sticking "rubber" in the subway, a fine of 1 thousand local dollars will be thrown in.
In four days, I met two people with white plates around their necks: “I was trashing.”
For throwing a cigarette butt past the urn, in addition to a fine, they are often sentenced to a "link to the janitors": a week to clean up parks and beaches.
6 thousand rubles. pays the "criminal", who forgot to wash off the water in the public toilet, and when trying to cope with a small need in the elevator of a residential house, a special detector is triggered - the doors are blocked and a signal is sent to the police.
Among the very exotic laws - prohibitions on feeding pigeons on the street, public singing and even excessive watering of houseplants (!): it is believed that an abundance of water attracts mosquitoes.
In order to avoid fires, smokers can not carry lighters in the subway, otherwise they will be fined 5 thousand Singapore dollars.
In general, there is a thought: no matter how you try, you will definitely break something.
That’s not true at all,” Mohammed Kabir-Kajariya, the owner of the local travel agency, tries to reassure me.
Especially fantastic laws exist only on paper, and in the last twenty years I have not seen anyone attracted to their violation.
Why do they persist?
So that citizens do not relax.
Compliance with the basic rules is strictly monitored.
For example, if a minor is sold cigarettes in a kiosk, then everything along the chain will be punished: the owner of the store will pay a huge amount, the offender himself will receive blows with sticks on the “back”, and the seller will also be beaten and imprisoned.
It is because of such strict laws that offenses in Singapore are very rare.
Is that justified?
Back in the seventies, we had chaos on the roads - motorists ignored traffic lights, drove as they wanted, sat drunk at the wheel.
After the introduction of fines for the year, everything calmed down.
Now the driver, having drunk a portion of whiskey, knows that if they stop, the policeman will not be released for a bribe, they will impose a fine in the amount of the apartment cost and will be sent to prison for years.
To many foreigners, a city-state in Southeast Asia seems like a kind of concentration camp.
In 1993, the American writer William Gibson called Singapore "Disneyland with the death penalty" - a guest from the United States was horrified by the general wealth of the inhabitants, "a frighteningly clean airport" and "cultured nature."
Saying such things are unnatural, look artificial, and in principle should not be.
The first days in Singapore and rightly afraid to throw a piece of paper on the sidewalk, you catch yourself if you went to the subway with ice cream.
But then you come to the "Little India", and suddenly - the "break pattern": at the bus stop are plastic cups.
