Nothing sacred?
The Trump White House is now targeting the Statue of Liberty.
The most reliable sign of regime change is when he begins to fight with the statues.
Americans understand this as well as anyone else – hence the deliberately theatrical demolition of a statue of Saddam Hussein in Firdos Square in Baghdad in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump administration’s key ideologues, no doubt knew what he was doing when he carried a symbolic axe over the Statue of Liberty during a fierce dispute with CNN journalist Jim Acosta over the president’s proposals to sharply reduce legal migration.
Let's be honest, Miller didn't try the statue himself.
Crowds of boat owners and artists depicting the Statue of Liberty would lynch him if he tried to do so.
But he attacked its meaning, and especially the meaning attributed to it in 1903, 17 years after the completion of the monument, when Emma Lazarus’ poems were added to the pedestal.
As Miller grumbled at Acosta, “I don’t want to go deep into history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you are talking about was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.”
Miller put the facts right, but as he said himself, it’s not really about the story.
It’s about the current sound of Lazarus’s astounding words, the only ones in which the state invites not any immigrants, but the poorest: “Your tired, your poor, / your crowds dreaming to breathe freely, / The miserable dregs of your abundant shores.”
Never before have "unfortunate scum" been so visible on our screens.
Miller was not engaged in literary studies - he made it clear that in America, Trump these people are not expected.
This dispute about the meaning of the statue is part of a wider political and cultural war: it is really a dispute about the meaning of America.
Lazarus – and her friends who fought to put her words on the base of the statue after her death – knew very well that they were committing a completely political act.
The sculpture was intended to mark the connection between the French and American republics with the help of a banal classical figure - the female image of Freedom.
Lazarus changed its meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract, she has a voice.
And she got a completely different name: Mother of the Exiled.
The combination of the poem and the image was a brilliant feminist move and a crushing attack on American nativism.
And how Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right though to change it back.
The loud-mouthed Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist who heralded Trump’s arrival, reasoned in 2010 that Liberty was inviting no one, rather it was an early neoconservative carrying the flame of America to a world in darkness: “Freedom is moving forward.
It carries the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not needed to light the way to the United States.”
Against the usual Limbo really got to the point here.
The meaning of the statue depends solely on the angle of view.
The great creative achievement of Lazarus was to see her as she would be seen by exhausted, unhappy, but hopeful people on the decks of ships after a long and often arduous voyage.
It means literally looking at the world through the eyes of people who are seeking refuge and a chance for a better life.
Her statue answers them with the words of hope and hospitality they dream of hearing.
And, of course, this is not the prospect that Miller and Trump will ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is needed not to illuminate the path, but to incite hatred, which is the only source of their power.
