Blocking critics on Facebook: don’t run for public office if you’re not ready to listen to criticism from voters
The founder of our country understood what a critical press is.
The Americans loved George Washington, but this did not prevent them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he didn’t shut his mouth to his critics.
In 1783, Washington said, “We can take away freedom of speech, and we, deaf and dumb, will be led like sheep to the slaughter.”
Now I’m going to go to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who should try to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s subordinates blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subordinates called this lawsuit insignificant, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "well, what".
“It’s just Facebook,” many will say.
But it's also important.
And this is especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He is a surprisingly popular Republican governor in a Democratic-dominated state.
He is in second place in the approval rating among the 50 governors of the country.
Hogan is not a reactionary.
He has shown a firm hand in running the state and a commitment to his principles.
He also deftly uses Facebook as a primary means of communicating with his constituents and jokingly displays his bald post-chemotherapy head on his page.
Therefore, blocking people who come to the governor’s page – which is declared as an official public forum and is run by administration officials for taxpayers’ money – is unnecessary and ultimately harmful.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Press Secretary Amelia Ches defended the governor’s actions, arguing that blocking comments is simply their moderation.
But it’s too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers, and haters on the internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are real people, not trolls - a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who appeal to their elected leaders.
All of them say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing to the fact that Hogan is a Catholic.
Lakshmi’s lawyer, Sarma Ramana of Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
“I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of reaction to hate crimes and other recent news,” she wrote in the comments section of the Post article.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same topic, some immediately say it’s a so-called hoax, instead of admitting that they’re dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens.”
What the governor’s subordinates call a “concentrated spam attack,” others would probably call an “active life stance.”
In the Facebook era, it’s easy to edit your image by simply blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
This is much less dusty work than before, when it required sending people, collecting and burning newspapers with critical fronts, or arresting and gaging protesters.
But that’s exactly what’s happening right now, only in numbers.
Hogan is not the first official to be criticized for not wanting to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who were banned from his Twitter account.
One of the first landmark decisions on this topic was made this week in Virginia.
According to U.S. District Judge James K. Casheris of Alexandria, the chairman of the Loudon County Supervisory Board violated the First Amendment by banning a voter from his Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, Republican Governor Matt Bavin was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union for his behavior on Facebook and Twitter.
It must not be so difficult.
In Washington’s time, the era of affordable postal spending made about the same upheaval as the Internet today.
From 1776 to 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters greatly undermined his authority.
And even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the pseudonyms “Yurikola”, “Valerius”, “Belizarius” and “Portius” wrote letters to newspapers mocking Washington’s decision.
According to historical documents compiled by the George Washington Papers online project, his office was inundated with petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Trade and Navigation.
But he did not try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lies at the very foundation of our state.
And true leadership means agreeing to it.
