Poverty and death in Indonesia’s ‘golden land’
When cooking dinner, Bardina Degei does not use the stove.
She rarely even uses the pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotala, the capital of Paniai district in the rebellious Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually just puts a sweet potato, which is called "note" here, right into the hearth.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is taken out and eaten with impatient, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the earthen floor – she has no furniture – and it is here that she does her housework, such as washing her clothes with muddy water from a nearby swamp.
The toilet is a bucket in a room without a roof.
She is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, so she was not assigned to work in the field.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: many men in this village are unemployed, many drink, and there are soldiers.
“No one dares to walk around the village after five in the evening,” she says.
It is a rare opportunity to look at everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was annexed to Indonesia in 1969 after a dubious referendum, when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote, publicly raising their hands in front of the occupying troops.
The existing movement for independence from the Netherlands has quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which retains tight control over the region without allowing foreign journalists and human rights defenders.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, and the independent state of Papua New Guinea occupies the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a city as remote as it is abandoned; the road here includes an hour and a half flight from Jayapura, the administrative center of the province, to Nabira, and then a five-hour shake in a hired car.
There is no public transport here.
The city of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences; the roofs of corrugated steel are painted rusty in a variety of reddish shades.
Few Indonesians got here, not to mention journalists, and almost none of the foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christian missionaries, the mee pago worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes.
“It was unusual for us to wear these clothes,” Degei says, pointing to his bright, hand-woven turban, dark skirt and bright shirt.
“We used to only carry leaves on our bodies.”
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of its population living below the poverty line and child mortality and literacy rates among the worst in Asia.
It is also the golden land of Indonesia.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just sixty miles from Paniai, a mountainous province roughly the size of New Jersey, home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua boasts forest reserves, the value of which is estimated at $ 78 billion.
These riches, however, entail one misfortune for the Papuans, ensuring that Indonesia’s powerful armed forces maintain their strangling presence here.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, between 1998 and 2004, Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units, including up to $150,000 to one officer.
The demands for greater autonomy on the part of the Papuans threaten the existence of this golden vein and are ruthlessly suppressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by Indonesian military forces since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned.
According to the Asian Commission on Human Rights, the massacres in the indigenous highlands of Papua in the 1970s can be considered genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
“We will lose everything,” a report published in 2016 by the Diocese of Brisbane, contains evidence of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as summary executions, torture – particularly frequent, as claimed in another report, rape and electric shocks – and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” Andreas Harsono, a researcher in Indonesia, told Human Rights Watch.
Nuts tightened as Papua's resources attracted an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's 3.5 million population is 83% Christian, but demographics change as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the densely populated Indonesian islands of Java, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese shops, "varunga", sell fried chicken and a mixture of "gado-gado" vegetables served with peanut sauce.
The locals are trying to keep up with the competition.
“Migrants started selling chicken and vegetables cheaper in the traditional market than the indigenous people of Papua,” explains Abet Yow, a twenty-four-year-old native of Paniai who moved to Jayapura, the provincial capital, for work.
“Because of this, the indigenous people of Papua – the mother-mother (women) of Papua – have lost their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 presidential campaign.
On his way to the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, the former carpenter enlisted the support of 27 of Papua’s 29 districts, including Paniai.
But in Papua, almost nothing has changed, and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Djokovic, expecting him to fulfill our hopes of restoring justice,” he said.
In fact, just two months after the October inauguration of Djokovic, Paniai survived the tragedy.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols at a campfire in Enarotala when two Indonesian soldiers broke out of the darkness on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them to turn on the lights.
According to local pastor Javedt Tebay, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone and after a while returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and eyewitnesses, soldiers who were drunk chased the children and beat them with rifle butts.
Then one of the soldiers shot at a group of children.
One child, sixteen-year-old Julianus Eimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby government election commission building, and the next day the situation escalated.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football pitch in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They brought with them ritual hunting bows and performed the waita, a dance of the Papuan Mee Pago tribe: running in circles and depicting bird singing.
Some protesters began throwing stones at the police station and military base.
When the situation escalated, soldiers on internal radio communication were ordered: “If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them,” as it was claimed in an official document seen by TIME magazine correspondents but not published in local media.
Fifty-six-year-old Jeremias Kayamé, the head of the Kego Koto district in Enarotala, felt the danger approaching and called for calm, appealing to the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen to him.
“When I turned around, a bullet suddenly hit my left wrist,” he told TIME magazine, standing on the porch of his brightly colored wooden house.
Kayama still doesn’t know who fired the shot, but says the bullet came from the side of the line of the assembled soldiers.
“There was a crowd, there were a lot of shots,” he adds.
A local resident of Alfius, Youwa, was hit three times, according to his cousin, who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran up to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Johannes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
General Yotje Mende, a senior police inspector in Papua, told reporters that his officers were only “defending” their base because it was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,” said Papua Police Commissioner Pujo Sulistiyo in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
The news of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the next day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing condolences to the families of the victims and vowing to address the issue of historic abuses of power in Papua.
“I want this situation to be resolved immediately so that it never happens again in the future,” he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Viranto said he would establish a non-judicial organization to end historic human rights violations.
But there were excuses almost immediately.
“Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some of them took place in the nineties or at the beginning of zero.
The fact is that we certainly want to address these violations, but there are procedures that need to be followed,” he said.
Wiranto then backed down, speaking to TIME magazine on June 5 in Jakarta, and said he had no plans to set up an organization to handle complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “It will all be decided in court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the United Nations of “crimes against humanity” in connection with the deaths of more than 1,000 people during a bloody vote for East Timor’s independence in 1999, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of Paniai met such statements with grim mistrust.
“I’ve been questioned four times in the last three years, but there’s been absolutely no change,” Johannes says.
“I am tired.”
He says that years later he still lives in fear.
“I’m scared,” he says.
“I’m afraid of being arrested by the military, I’m afraid of being shot.”
His brother Jacobus also expressed the opinion that the inhabitants of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four victims.
“After we buried the bodies, the military came after me,” he says.
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in the nearby Paniai district of Deiai.
In a clash between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to help take an unconscious man to hospital, one person was killed and 17 others were injured, including children.
A man, twenty-four-year-old Ravianus Dove, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the office of the construction site owned by the company.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the officers, who in response fired warning shots.
But locals claim that a mobile brigade (Indonesian special forces) began shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“We were in such a panic, we’re afraid of retaliation,” 29-year-old Domingu Badia, who lives near the hospital, told TIME magazine.
“I stayed at home for two days.”
The Deiai Parliament demanded that the officers involved in the incident be called to account and that the mobile police brigade be withdrawn from the region.
Paniai has always been a sore spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of significant development causes discontent of the Mei, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes scattered throughout the green-covered central highlands of Papua.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), an insurgent army that claims to defend the rights of Papuans by staging sporadic attacks and raids with kidnappings of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM executives come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and unjustifiably detained by the military in recent years in Paniai under the pretext of “defending national independence”.
Some never came back.
Among the population of Papua Paniai is considered a “sad, forgotten place”.
Poverty increases discontent.
A small portion of rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
Bread is not available to the same extent.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly, a note, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Agriculture is the work of women, each of whom can care for four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Usually they save most of the harvest for the family, and the rest is sold in the local market.
Ten note tubers cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has increased between indigenous Papuans and new migrants who arrived in large numbers following the introduction of new flights to Nabire Airport.
Few existing vacancies usually go to more educated and wealthy migrants.
Papuans rarely have enough money or the necessary skills to run their own competitive business.
“Young people don’t want to stay in the village... because there’s no work, no money,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps Papua away from the eyes of the rest of the world.
In addition, restrictions on the work of international media remain severe.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basil Longchamp were deported from Papua for “insufficient coordination with relevant organizations” despite being given rare permits to conduct videotaping.
According to Felim Kine, deputy director for Asia at Human Rights Watch, promises made during the election campaign of Djokovic to lift restrictions on the work of the media in order to promote transparency and development have not been fulfilled.
“Now, foreign journalists trying to report from the rebellious eastern Indonesian provinces, Papua and West Papua face new dangers: visa denials and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of press attention means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely limited to Papua’s immediate neighbors.
In March, six Pacific states — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands — asked the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “diverse and widespread violations” in Papua, including the Paniya shooting.
The same countries have supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arramanata Nasir dismissed the group's statement, telling reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and a free press, so it would be difficult to hide evidence of human rights violations."
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention to the situation.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by Dutch Human Rights Ambassador Kiys Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, locals broke their silence, pleading: “We want freedom,” according to a source who was also present at the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia will hold a new presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Djokovic again.
“The Djokovics are a man with good intentions, but they’re surrounded by people involved in the Paniai shooting,” said Gobai, chairman of the tribe’s council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai, in addition to living in the shadow of the threat from the greedy army, are mired in poverty, and their education and health care are in poor condition.
Gobai says that the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote for Jokowi to be a debt that he must pay.
“They don’t want money, they just want justice,” he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai shooting carried out the last symbolic act of disobedience: they buried the body of one of the victims on a plot of land directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice will probably never prevail, they will at least not let the guilty forget their crimes.
“They killed a member of our family,” Jacobus says, without raising his head.
“What else did we have to do?”
