EPA Chief Pruitt Refuses to Delay Obama’s Emissions Reduction Rules
The day after the lawsuit filed by 15 states, the head of the Environmental Protection Agency reversed his decision to postpone the implementation of Obama’s rules designed to reduce emissions of air pollutants and lead to the formation of smog.
Pruitt explained his decision by the fact that now his agency more than under previous administrations, listens to the needs of environmental regulators of individual states.
He made no mention of the action brought against his previous position before the Federal Court of Appeals.
The dispute revolved around the October 1 deadline by which states must ensure compliance with 2015 standards for ozone at ground level.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would defer compliance for one year to give his department more time to study the plan and avoid “inconsistency with local decisions or obstacles to economic growth.”
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma’s attorney general before he was appointed by President Trump, has long been known as a consistent opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
After moving to Washington, Pruitt repeatedly blocked or delayed the introduction of norms that were opposed by the chemical or gas-oil industry.
An unexpected change of course on Wednesday is another legal defeat of the course taken by Puitt to return to the previous norms.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA chief had exceeded his authority in trying to delay the Obama administration’s enforcement of a rule requiring oil and gas companies to track and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday evening, Pruitt suggested that by dramatically changing course regarding ozone standards, he was simply fulfilling the EPA’s duty to cooperate with states in the comprehensive process of timely implementation of the new standards.
“Under previous administrations, the EPA has often failed to meet deadlines, then waited for lawsuits from activist groups and others and discussed timelines in the course of settling the case,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through trials, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take seriously our charter and the power it gives us.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could at some point re-use his “deferral powers and other statutory powers” to ensure that the norms “jcyjdfys on a clear course and on all available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader review of the ozone rules.
The bill, approved by the House of Representatives last month, seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The Senate has not yet voted on the issue.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states filing a lawsuit against the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue legal pressure.
“The EPA’s change of course – following our lawsuits – is an important victory in the fight for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans, who are directly affected by the smog covering their cities,” Schneiderman said.
New York's lawsuit was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, as well as the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone occurs when ordinary pollutants from machinery, power plants, refineries, and chemical plants and other sources enter the atmosphere and react with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe respiratory problems in sensitive people, leading to thousands of premature deaths a year.
Health and environmental advocates welcomed Pruitt’s unexpected change of course.
“It’s sad to think about how much pressure it took to get this perfectly logical step from the person tasked with protecting the air we breathe,” said Laurie Ann Bird of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to resist the Trump administration’s ideological campaign to protect those who pollute the air and their special interests.”
