Murder at Morse Ford: Activists Will Lose Lynch Courts on Stage to Call for Justice
The 1948 Ford Mercury drove past spectators in Monroe, Georgia, and roared toward the small Morse Ford Bridge.
When a car carrying four black passengers and a white driver approached the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its path.
The main man - a middle-aged man in a suit in a thin strip - tightened his cigar and looked through the windshield.
Those inside trembled with fear.
"We need that nigger, Roger!" the man roared.
"Get him out of the car!"
The shrill screams broke the silence as a young black man was pulled out of the front seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene, which took place on July 22nd, is just a staging.
But when the neck of "Roger" was thrown a loop, almost all the audience really held their breath.
Since 2005, activists have been returning to the Morse Ford Bridge to re-lose the night when two black couples, Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and May Murray Dorsey, were lynched by the puppeteers in 1946.
No one was convicted of these murders.
“It’s amazing that in all these years, no one has been arrested — even though we see them next to us; even though we know who they are,” says Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the production.
“It is a stain on our history and a stone on our souls.”
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia congressman who has fought for human rights his entire life.
For him, the play is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to the people of Monroe that injustice has never been corrected.
“We want an investigation, we want closure, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we have to get justice,” he said.
“We can’t move on to healing and reconciliation until we get justice.”
The coroner covers the body of one of the lynching victims at Morse Ford on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI materials obtained by NBC News, more than 50 people in Monroe and neighboring counties were suspected of involvement in the lynching.
But no one was ever charged.
Although the suspects have been at large for decades, human rights activists say the city has always known two related lynching motives: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling first allowed black citizens to vote in the primaries, which were to take place that summer.
Approximately during the same election, according to the FBI, black executor Roger Malcolm stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, apparently because of a woman, in a fight.
Brooks says that Hester was rumored to have slept with Malcolm Dorothy's wife, and that the child she was about to give birth to was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a major white landowner, paid $600 bail to free Malcolm from prison.
He went to prison with Dorothy and their cousins May Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they drove out of the prison and drove up to the Morse Ford Bridge, a mob of vigilantes surrounded the car.
“It turns out that Harrison organized and commanded the killings,” the FBI said in a report.
“It’s also clear that there was collusion between state and city law enforcement who not only took part in the killings, but also destroyed the evidence and hid the identities of the witnesses.”
Brooks calls it short.
“It was an attack on the right to vote,” he said.
“They were all killed to send a message to black people in the city: if you sign up and vote, it will be the same for you.”
For almost a decade, Cassandra Green has directed an annual performance reproducing that lynching at Morse Ford Bridge.
Her performance is vivid, it captures the viewer and tells about the deep racism, which, as many would like to believe, is no longer in America.
It’s hard to watch and even harder to turn away, but Green believes that’s the main thing.
“We don’t want to talk about Lynch courts because they show us our own ugliness,” she says.
"But I can't build a relationship with you if you don't hear me or hear what I've been through."
Rehearsals for this year’s play began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors – a dozen white, the rest black – gathered indoors and listened to the play’s review, which had been polished over the years.
Wade Marboe was the director along with Greene.
He played the role of the main member of the clan for several years, but says that the role has not become easier.
“I think I got dirty because he’s not the person I am,” Marboe says.
“But I think it’s very important to remember this story because we don’t want to go back to that time.”
In the room, the actors Darius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcolm and Barnett Hester, repeat their roles.
The show begins with Malcolm, angry that Hester is sleeping with his wife Dorothy, screaming and pushing him.
"I said, nigga, get out of my house!"
Raskon screams in response.
It's a hit.
And at the same time, everyone (at least all black actors) is bursting with laughter.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What is it?" asks Ascona.
He's worried and embarrassed.
Am I overreacting?
"No," Greene says through laughter.
“I just don’t think white people said ‘nigga’ back then.”
“Yes,” laughed one of the black men.
"You've got to get a solid 'r'."
And also the energy in the room changes: discomfort is replaced by a sense of companionship.
Everyone should do everything right, not only for the sake of the play, but also for the sake of the memory of the four people killed.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Raskona says the word for the letter "n", it turns out clear and sharp.
No man laughs.
The show ends abruptly and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then silence.
A woman in mourning black clothes stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billy Holiday's sad song "Strange Fruit".
Her voice is interrupted by the word.
A hundred yards from her, fifty spectators wipe tears and sweat from their eyes.
Among the spectators almost equal number of black and white.
One couple came from Ithaca, New York to see the show; many live very close by.
They endured Georgia’s heavy spirits for nearly eight hours as Brooks led them on a pilgrimage to the tombs of the Malcolms and Dorsey.
Up to this point, the murders were just history, but now that they are standing in the same place where people were lynched, it seems that their ghosts are in the air right now.
When the last note of the song subsides, Green invites people to come closer and examine the bodies.
The children bend over to their heads, touch the paint depicting blood, and the still bodies and whisper something to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” murmurs one little boy, as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Green thanks the audience, and suddenly everything ends.
Actors drop ropes from their necks and wipe away tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbo, a man in a suit who played the main puppeteer.
Nick Rascona hugs the other two actors and suddenly, crying, falls into their arms: the emotional burden of the performance finally fell on him.
"It's all right," whispered one of the women.
“We know your heart is good.
You had a reason for that.”
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta is busy discussing the play with a black couple they have just met.
Denise Daplinsky finds it difficult to find the words to describe how she feels after the performance.
“It’s hard to listen to these horrible, horrible words, and actions... of people who look like you and who do it because they look like you,” she says.
“After that, I think the lynchings are still happening,” she adds, “only now it’s called being shot by the police.”
In the other corner of the room, Tyrone Brooks, who remembers his work as a human rights defender, captured the general attention.
He says he's already started planning next year's show.
“The play excites us because it not only describes the horror of what we’ve been through, but also teaches us,” he says.
“Because if you don’t learn from this lesson, it could happen again.
Those who do not study their history, who do not know their history, are doomed to repeat it.
