Coe praised the “sincere” apology of Russia in connection with the doping scandal
International track and field specialist Sebastian Coe on Thursday praised what he called Russia's sincere apologies for the doping scandal, but reiterated that now was not the right time to allow the country to compete in sports again.
Russian representative of the athletics Federation Dmitry Shlyakhtin said at the Congress of the International Association of Athletics Federations, which was held on the eve of the World Championships in athletics, that the suspension of his country from sports competitions was fair and that he was determined to fight doping.
He apologized to “all athletes whose gold and silver medals were stolen from the competition.”
Despite his comments, the Congress of the International Association of Athletics Federations voted to maintain the suspension imposed in November 2015 after the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) published a report on found evidence of state-funded doping.
“It seemed to me that today’s response, today’s report, was very sincere,” Coe, president of the International Association of Athletics Federations, told reporters.
“The whole council and the whole congress liked ... that the Russian Federation itself admits that it has been going through extremely hot times and is now doing everything possible to take care of the restructuring of the federation.”
Coe said he also “liked” that Russia had agreed to the criteria for its recovery.
“I think it’s been a very constructive day and that we’re moving forward, but Congress supports the recommendations of the special committee that now is not the time to restore Russia’s rights,” Coe said.
“In the next few months, we must do everything to resolve this situation.
Our guiding principle was our desire to separate clean athletes from the stained system,” he added.
Nineteen Russian athletes who meet the strict criteria of the International Association of Athletics Federations will participate under a neutral flag in the World Championships in Athletics, which will begin on Friday in London.
The head of the special commission of the International Association of Athletics Federations, Rune Andersen, said on Monday that a number of requirements have yet to be met to restore Russia.
As he told reporters in London after the report made at the Council of the International Association of Athletics Federations, drug testing is still not carried out in sufficient volume, and suspended coaches are still quietly doing their work.
