How football’s financial rules will affect Neymar’s move to Paris
The rules, aimed at preventing unlimited spending by European football clubs, will not prevent the world record-setting transfer of Neymar from Spanish “Barcelona” to French “Paris Saint-Germain”.
Whatever the consequences may be further down the chain, for Paris Saint-Germain by UEFA, the governing body that controls European football, whose power it is to ban teams from participating in the prestigious Champions League tournament.
From the financial fair play rules introduced by UEFA in 2011, it follows that PSG will eventually have to show that Neymar’s transfer was financed without major losses.
Barcelona were paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to release the Brazilian from the contract, and Neymar will receive a salary that will reach tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some financial aspects of Neymar’s move to France.
PSG can certainly fork out to hire Neymar and add him to the galaxy of other stars, given the team’s funding from Qatar’s energy-rich ruling family.
Clubs have the right to spend large sums to acquire players, but they have to balance them at the expense of legitimate sources of income to reach the threshold of profitability in their football business.
FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French footballer believed that clubs that were in huge debt in their pursuit of success were in fact cheating and risking ruin in the event that banks or owners stopped financing.
In 2011, FFP ceased to focus on the debts of the clubs and instead switched to tracking their losses.
As a result of this change, the business model initially used by Roman Abramovich at Chelsea in 2003 – buying a club with good potential and then spending heavily to improve the team and build a global brand – has become a difficult plan.
During this three-year evaluation period, which is exciting in 2018, clubs can incur losses of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million.
And despite Platini’s disgraceful removal from the presidency in 2015, his successor at UEFA, Aleksander Ceferin, is still determined to rein in excessive spending.
“Of course, FFP is alive and we are moving forward to tighten the rules,” Andrea Traverso, who controls FFP at UEFA, told the Associated Press last week.
Although PSG will pay Neymar’s contract at one time, he can distribute this amount for reporting for the entire term of his contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, so the transfer value can be shown in the annual report as a cost of 44.4 million euros over the next five years.
During the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, severe sanctions were imposed on PSG, as well as on Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City.
PSG was fined <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>60 million ($82 million at that rate), which was later reduced to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>20 million, and was ordered to limit its Champions League squad during the 2014–15 season to 21 players instead of the usual 25.
UEFA is tracking clubs that may try to outsmart its financial inspections by inflating their revenue at the expense of companies linked to the club’s owners.
Although the Qatari company could sponsor PSG, but if the amount of financing was considered to exceed standard market prices, UEFA would not allow it to be considered a legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount of PSG’s funding from the Qatar Tourism Authority was inflated.
It was reported that part of Neymar’s earnings at PSG could come in the form of payments from the organizing committee of the 2022 World Cup in Qatar.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 deny that Neymar will become an ambassador for the World Cup, and such a maneuver could easily be detected by UEFA inspectors.
Past sanctions imposed on PSG mean that UEFA will be even more closely monitoring any attempts to circumvent the rules.
As reported on Thursday, people familiar with the situation, UEFA did not have preliminary discussions with PSG about the transfer of Neymar.
They spoke to the Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorized to discuss PSG’s position.
According to the latest published report, in 2015-1016, PSG received more than 10 million euros in profit with a turnover of 542.4 million euros.
The accounts for the last financial year have not yet been published.
PSG expects that Neymar’s arrival will be a favorable ground for sponsorship deals, the sale of paraphernalia and T-shirts with the team logo.
The club expects turnover to grow by at least 30 percent as a result of hiring a new player.
Undoubtedly angry that one of the best players is leaving, the Spanish league tried to interfere with the transfer of Neymar, saying that PSG would violate the financial fair play.
“This is an obvious case of financial doping, with the club and the state,” La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS, referring to Qatar as the ultimate owner of PSG.
Arsenal coach Ars<0xC3><0xA8>ne Wenger, whose club belongs to the American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's doubts about the club's state funding.
“These are all consequences of equity participation, and it has completely changed the landscape of football over the last fifteen years,” Wenger said on Thursday.
“When the club belongs to the country, everything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to comply with financial fair play, because the country can have many ways and many reasons to be represented by such a serious player.
The manner and place of taking the oath of office shall be determined by the President.
Where and how new Russian citizens will swear allegiance to the Russian Federation will be determined by the president - such amendments to the second reading of the relevant law were developed by the State Duma committee on legislation and state construction.
A week ago, the deputies planned to directly determine the procedure for taking the oath in the law.
From the solemn oath will be released children under 18 years, as well as incapacitated, follows from the amended text of the amendments to the bill "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation" (available "News"), which the Committee on July 11 will consider before the second reading at its meeting.
The idea of introducing the oath of citizenship of the Russian Federation instead of the formal signing of documents was supported by President Vladimir Putin on June 6 during a meeting with the speaker of the state Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The deputies formalized this idea in the form of an amendment to the second reading of the bill providing for the abolition of the decision on the issuance of citizenship to those who were subsequently convicted of a number of crimes of a terrorist or extremist nature: for example, for public calls for terrorism or its public justification in the media or on the Internet (part 2 of Article 205.2 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation), as well as for the theft of an aircraft, a train or a train.
According to the bill, its logic was as follows: when drawing up documents for citizenship, a person signs a promise to comply with Russian legislation - having taken the path of extremism, he violates this promise.
In April, the bill was submitted to the State Duma by the leaders of the Duma factions Vladimir Vasilyev (“United Russia”), Gennady Zyuganov (KPRF), Vladimir Zhirinovsky (LDPR), Sergei Mironov (“Fair Russia”) and the speaker of the State Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
On 19 May, the deputies adopted it in the first reading.
Last week, the State Duma Committee on State Construction and Legislation approved the text of the bill for the second reading, but now it has been revised again.
Now it says that the order of taking the oath will be established by the President of the Russian Federation.
Earlier, parliamentarians were going to describe the procedure directly in the law "On Citizenship of the Russian Federation", indicating that the ceremony should be held in a solemn atmosphere in front of the state emblem and flag of Russia in the presence of a representative of the Ministry of Internal Affairs.
However, it was not clear from the text of the bill where such an event should take place - the list of places where the Russian coat of arms can be placed is regulated by the relevant federal constitutional law.
These include courts, cabinets of heads of state authorities of subjects, municipalities, judges, prosecutors, heads of federal executive bodies, etc.
Most likely, it could be the registry.
To make a solemn oath wishing to obtain citizenship of the Russian Federation will be after officials check their documents.
But a person will receive a Russian passport only after taking the oath, it follows from the revised text.
A week ago, the draft said that the oath should precede the signing of the decree.
The updated text says that Russia will be sworn in at the age of 18, not at 14.
There is a rule that the oath will be exempt from incapacitated or limited incapacitated, as well as those who can not pronounce, read or personally sign the text of the oath.
In addition, the President of the Russian Federation has the right to release from this procedure and "other persons",
Also, the updated draft law prescribes a special procedure for admission to Russian citizens of residents of Ukraine, who are considered to be native speakers of the Russian language.
They will have to officially renounce their Ukrainian citizenship by submitting a corresponding application to the authorized body of Ukraine.
A notarized copy of the application will need to be handed over to Russian officials.
Renunciation of “foreign” citizenship, as it is now, will not be required if it is provided for by an international treaty or if it is impossible “for reasons beyond one’s control”.
The corresponding amendment to the law was proposed by a group of deputies, including the first vice-speaker of the State Duma Ivan Melnikov (KPRF), Natalia Poklonskaya, Pavel Krasheninnikov and Airat Farrakhov (all - "United Russia").
I think many of you know that getting a certificate from Ukraine is unrealistic, simply impossible.
Accordingly, a lot of people are waiting for the decision of their fate regarding the citizenship of the Russian Federation, - explained the head of the Duma Committee on state construction and legislation Pavel Krasheninnikov (EP).
In addition, the text clarifies that restrictions on the employment of certain positions for foreigners will not apply to those who refused in writing from "other" citizenship and handed over the former passport to the Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia, but "for reasons beyond his control" he did not cease to be considered a citizen of another country.
Now foreigners are prohibited from holding positions in the municipal service, to be employed at facilities and in organizations whose activities are related to ensuring the security of Russia.
Also, a person with dual citizenship or a residence permit of another country may not become a deputy of the State Duma or a member of the Federation Council.
It is planned that the law should enter into force from September 1, 2017, by which time the necessary by-laws should be ready.
Nostalgia becomes a niche in "The Hot American Summer" and "Comrade Detective"
The current iteration of the story nostalgically recalls both the glorious days of the characters in the 80s; the grunge era in the 90s (about the time when the outstanding masters David Wayne and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy "The State" for MTV); and about herself - that is, about 2001 to the year, before her stars as Elisa Povett.
As a fact of culture, it is simultaneously the elevation and embodiment of our era with its constant reminders from Facebook.
But as a franchise, it seems anachronistic.
“The First Day of Camp” was surprisingly good, and not just because of its absurdist humor (including the original story of a can of vegetables voiced by H. John Benjamin).
The result doubles the main joke: middle-aged actors play sexually preoccupied children who have just reached adulthood; thanks to this, the inability to return to the joke becomes part of the joke.
“Ten Years Later,” where adults have already played adults, has less deep emotional roots, and its parody is more haphazard and includes riffs from 90s stalker films like “Hands rocking the cradle.”
In one episode, the character takes out an Apple Powerbook, four-wheeled roller skates, and "a bunch of other things from 1991."
Many of the storylines are the same.
The good-natured Coop (Showalter), now a writer, has still not achieved reciprocity from Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn’t broken up with his virginity.
And then there’s the insane and despicable conspiracy involving Ronald Reagan (also Showalter), now instigated by George H.W. Bush (a tried-and-true parody by Michael Ian Blake).
As always, the best part of the franchise is the retreat from it.
It’s especially funny to see the eternally young Rudd singing Matt Dillon’s song from Lonesome, whose character, former big man Andy, now looks like an old man.
The success of this franchise could be brought by random madness in the spirit of the recursive series “Seven Up”, until it reaches what, in my opinion, would be its logical conclusion: “Hot American summer: twenty years later”, where in the last scene the whole company would go to the cinema for the premiere of the film “Hot American summer”.
“Comrade Detective” on the Amazon turns to a different type of nostalgia: memories of the Cold War from “Americans,” “Blonde Blast,” or even “The Flash” with her images of the struggle between East and West.
This comedy, created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka with director Reese Thomas, depicts a 1980s Romanian police drama about two policemen in Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the Marxist-Leninist path.
The main roles - who saw the life of Gregor and idealist Joseph - are performed by Florin Piersik Jr. and Corneliu Ulich, and their dialogues in English were voiced by Channing Tatum (he is also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a brilliant idea.
But just an idea.
There are a few visual jokes (policemen spend time watching a chess match as Americans might watch football).
The team of famous voices behind the scenes - among them Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloe Sevigny - makes it interesting to play "guess the voice".
But "Comrade Detective" is so clinging to the plausibility of a clumsy propaganda drama - there's even a killer in a Ronald Reagan mask - that often looks like it.
Six long episodes are long, and it’s not funny very often.
If it were made shorter, Comrade Detective would be better able to handle his agitprop satire; for example, every time Gregor and Joseph come to the American embassy, there are two fat people sitting in the lobby devouring a bunch of hamburgers.
To an imaginary communist spectator, this image tells us that Western culture can make anything into a glutton.
Fictional Romanian filmmakers are not so wrong: We do so even with our own recent history, and with them too.
