The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
It is expected that the Bank of England will later announce that interest rates will not change after weak economic growth and weakening inflation caused rumors of a possible increase to subside.
The Bank of England warned that economic growth would remain sluggish and left interest rates unchanged amid growing pressure on family incomes.
The Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with a smaller number of committee members this month calling for a rate hike because weak economic growth weakened support for the hike.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank capped its forecasts at 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018 and warned that pressure on family incomes would continue, while inflation is still expected to rise to around 3% in the fall.
However, the bank warned that rate hikes in the next few years would be necessary to control Brexit-induced inflation, and said borrowing costs would likely have to be raised more than expected in financial markets.
The committee also voted to abandon part of the huge package of economic development measures launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
Starting next February, the bank will close the emergency financing plan, under which it provides banks with cheap loans, although he said that now he will have to provide another 15 billion pounds under this plan - up to 115 billion pounds.
In the rate decision protocol, the bank said, “According to the MPC’s main projections, gross domestic product (GDP) growth is likely to remain slow in the near term, while pressure on real household incomes continues to affect consumption.”
On the subject of rates, he reiterated that in order to halt inflation, “some tightening of financial policy” would be required, at a “slightly larger” rate than markets expect.
At the moment, markets are predicting a first increase in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
But the bank stressed that all increases would be “gradual” and “limited.”
The bank’s forecasts for growth this year and next year are lower than those made in May, which were equal to 1.9% and 1.7%.
The bank left its forecast unchanged at 1.8% in 2018.
After this news, sterling fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to 1.31 US dollars and 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision not to change the rate was made after the recent disappointing growth figures weakened the increased expectation of an increase; GDP then grew by 0.3% in the second quarter against 0.2% in the previous three months.
According to the representative of the bank, growth, apparently, will remain at the level of 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will begin to increase slightly at the end of the year.
The bank’s latest report on inflation gave little cause for rejoicing to households hit by high inflation and very small wage increases: according to the bank, the pressure will increase before declining.
The bank added that financial policy “cannot prevent” a good performance on earnings in the next few years, but expects wages to “significantly” recover by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy is also set to grow as a result of growing demand for British goods, due to the low pound exchange rate, which compensates for some of the reduced consumer spending.
The decision came a year after rates were cut to 0.25% last August following the shock results of the referendum on leaving the European Union, which caused the pound to fall.
The bank estimates it will likely take four years to fully impact prices and the economy.
Before the bank made its final decision on rates, there was a growing buzz around the supposed rate hike, as inflation was increasingly pressing on the already heavily pressured households: three members of the specialist committee asked to raise rates to 0.5% in July.
Last month, inflation fell to 2.6% from 2.9% in July, although the bank said the drop was expected and will be offset again in the coming months.
According to the bank, the higher figure compared to the planned 2% is entirely due to the low exchange rate of the pound.
