The state health service will prescribe a controversial drug for HIV 10000 people
Starting in September, patients will have access to a “revolutionary” drug for HIV prevention after a battle in the High Court over funding for the drug from the Public Health Service.
The National Health Service of England has announced that Pre-Exposure HIV Prevention (PrEP), a pill taken before sex that has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in people at risk by an average of 86 percent, will now be provided by the health service during the initial three-year trial period of approximately 10,000 people.
She agreed to finance the trial after an appeals court upheld a High Court ruling last year that argued the National Health Service had the ability to pay for PrEP, despite her claims that it should be funded by local authorities.
The move, announced on Thursday, was called “the most important innovation” by the president of the National Health Service of England, Simon Stevens, and the National AIDS Control Authority (NAT) called it a “turning point”.
Before the full launch of the programme across England by April 2018, venereal dispensaries in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start registering people, with even more dispensaries joining the programme in October.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PreEP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV infection among people at risk.
When taking PrEP before sex, there are enough certain drugs in the human body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken daily or no later than two hours before sex.
Patients eligible for the drug include homosexual and bisexual men, transgender people and people whose partners are HIV-positive and do not receive successful treatment.
The dispensaries will select suitable participants who have agreed to participate in the study, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals whose partners are not known whether their HIV status is being held back by antiretroviral therapy.
People living and assigned to a GP in England will also be able to apply for potential participation in the nearest venereological dispensary participating in the program.
The programme will cost <0xC2><0xA3>10m, and the NHS has signed a contract to supply the drug this week following an international procurement tender.
The study is structured in such a way as to assess all the possibilities of PrEP by collecting clinical data on who is the target audience of the drug, on its digestibility and application on a large scale.
“This critical innovation should complement and strengthen the large-scale and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in more than three decades of success in the fight against one of the greatest health threats facing humanity.
Deborah Gold, president of NAT (National AIDS Control Office), said: “This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if correctly targeted at people in need and at risk, makes it possible to change the situation with the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at risk for HIV, thanks to this study conducted in England at the expense of the National Health Service, will have access to a new tool that opens up new opportunities, the use of which a person can control himself without discussing it with a partner, which will lead to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this news.”
