Judges should be protected from presidents.
The Presidential Council for Human Rights (HRC), on behalf of Vladimir Putin, has developed proposals to strengthen the independence of the judiciary.
The HRC proposes to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts and to introduce their election.
For the courts of appeal and cassation instances, the HRC wants to introduce special districts that will not be tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The Supreme Court should also submit its proposals within the framework of the presidential mandate.
The HRC has completed the development of proposals that will strengthen the independence of Russian justice.
This work of the HRC was carried out on behalf of Vladimir Putin on January 3, 2017, which the president gave after a meeting with members of the council.
At the meeting with the council members on December 8, 2016, they discussed, among other things, individual cases of judicial arbitrariness, as well as problems of public control in places of detention of citizens (see Kommersant of December 9, 2016).
The work of the HRC resulted in 25 proposals that address both the independence of judges and the identification of judicial errors, as well as the financing of courts and legal education.
One of the ideas of the Kremlin’s human rights defenders is to limit the powers of the presidents of the courts to increase the independence of the other judges.
If the candidate for the position of judge successfully passed the competition and received the support of the judicial community, the chairman of the court, in the opinion of the HRC, must submit him for appointment, not having the right to refuse, as the law now allows.
It is also proposed to deprive the President of the right to distribute cases among judges.
To do this, experts admit, can specially written computer program.
The HRC also believes that the chairman has no right to “predetermine the results of the qualification certification of a judge, initiate his bringing to disciplinary responsibility, make decisions on the establishment of additional material payments”.
At the same time, the Presidential Council considers it necessary to proceed to the “election of the presidents of the courts by the judges themselves” and “endow them with powers for a relatively short period with mandatory rotation.”
Now all the presidents of the courts (from republican to district) are appointed for six years by the president on the proposal of the chairman of the Supreme Court of the Russian Federation.
In order to protect judges from the pressure of regional administrations, the HRC proposes to organize appeal and cassation in the courts of general jurisdiction in a new way.
Now their structure is tied to the administrative-territorial division in the Russian Federation.
The HRC says that "it is necessary to ensure the organization of individual courts of appeal and cassation not at the level of regional judicial bodies in the constituent entities of the Russian Federation, but in judicial districts."
Experts take as a basis the practice of arbitration courts.
There are “judicial districts” that do not coincide with the administrative division in the Russian Federation, but guarantee greater independence from regional officials who find it difficult to use “telephone law”.
The HRC proposes to strengthen the people’s jurors in order to consider some “categories of civil and administrative cases” with their participation.
For example, about the deprivation of parental rights, about reinstatement at work, about the protection of honor and dignity, about the deprivation of driving licenses, etc.
"These are only our proposals," explained HRC member, retired Constitutional Court judge Tamara Morshchakova.
She also recalled that the president's instruction was not only to the HRC, but also to the Supreme Court (Supreme Court), which has not yet disclosed its proposals.
There is still time for the execution of the order from the Armed Forces (among the co-executors - the Prosecutor General's Office and the Commissioner for Human Rights in the Russian Federation).
To report to Vladimir Putin on how effectively the independence of justice is ensured in the Russian Federation, the Chairman of the Armed Forces Vyacheslav Lebedev must before September 1.
Living the high life: semi-floor and clever design techniques have turned this small apartment in Earls Court into a spacious dwelling
Joan Lee, a former real estate banker, moved from a spacious home in Knightsbridge to an apartment in Earls Court in 2014.
The apartment is on the ground floor of a cute Queen Anne-style typical house, and in favor of the new design says that Joan did not pack her things and did not move again.
“I used to live with my ex in Knightsbridge on a much larger area,” says Joan.
“I was looking for something comparable for my money.
I was shown this apartment in Earls Court, and there were the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with her and offered her a price the same day.”
Since the first viewing, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
Initially, it was a one-bedroom apartment with a complex layout – to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen – and Joanna wanted to add storage space and a half-story to squeeze the maximum benefit from the generous height of the ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she says.
To this end, she hired Erfan Azadi of the Notting Hill-based architectural and design studio Duck & Shed to use 12.5-foot-tall ceilings to create a home that would not only be a successful project, but fit Joan for life.
The ceiling was not high enough to accommodate two rooms one above the other, so the architectural task was to create a half-story where one could stand at full height.
Erfan had to think creatively to cope with the brief.
“Working with steel structures is very difficult,” he explains.
“We had to arrange the rooms so that they were one above the other, and did not have to bend.
It was necessary not just to build a simple platform, but to bend the structures so that they were at the right height and allowed to use the premises from above and below.”
This solution allowed Erfan to arrange two full-sized rooms one above the other in a separate space – and much more interesting.
From the half-floor through a vintage copper light window from <0xC2><0xAB>Retrouvius» opens a view of the chic living room below.
Mirror furniture with a golden finish, silver accents and vintage lighting devices from Serge Mui set the style of the project.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding spectacle, space and light.
The short corridor is framed by mirrors to make it appear longer.
In the kitchen, the mirrored protective panel looks like a window to another room.
At the entrance, mirror cabinets are used to store all Joan's dishes.
To create the feeling of a more luxurious space, the beauty of the living room can enclose the kitchen when it is not used.
There is nothing new in the kitchen.
The uniqueness of this kitchen is that it is a sliding up door, like in a garage.
“Engineering art was involved here,” Erfan says of the steel-reinforced wood-fiber panel door.
“It’s equipped with a counterweight, so when you push the door up, it slides very easily.”
Thanks to the reasonable use of space and storage space, Joan received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and improved layout.
“After all, floor space is exactly what you’re going to sell, that is, what your property is valued at,” Erfan says.
Roughly speaking, a real estate agent will come in and make calculations based on floor area.
Here they were able to increase the area of the floors using quality materials that give the space a touch of luxury.
“Materials are what we touch, so they help build an emotional connection with the home,” Erfan says.
“No one falls in love with electrical wiring in walls.
It’s important, but it doesn’t touch the strings of our hearts.”
This is evidence that due to good design and increased footage, an apartment can turn from something ordinary into something amazing.
In fact, like Joan, you may decide to stay.
