The brothers are fighting for a real estate empire worth more than $ 500 million
Two brothers fight for one of Victoria’s largest empires in real estate trading worth more than $500 million – forty years after their Italian ancestors founded the dynasty.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin de Lutys lives in the Turak Palace through three doors from his younger brother Paul, who filed a lawsuit against him in the Supreme Court for the division of property and assets.
Paul wants to get out of the family business in 2014, but the Supreme Court is still in a heated dispute about the terms of the divorce.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 87 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, bought since their family bought a store on Smith Street in Collingwood in 1973.
There the family founded the firm "Westco Jeans", which grew into a network of 160 outlets.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
The money was invested in real estate, and the De Lutys family’s list of possessions today includes office buildings, development sites in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and in Mount Buller, and shopping centers in the suburbs.
By arrangement with Colin's late father - whom Paul describes as the "main driving force and dominant personality" of the De Lutys family - he owns about two-thirds of the company's assets, and Paul owns about one-third.
According to the court, this means that the property of Colin is 316 million, and Paul - 176 million.
The division of property and money became a stumbling block for Paul.
“The section proposed by Colin gives him, in my opinion, the best parts of the property,” he wrote in his first statement in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first hearings in the Supreme Court were held.
The brothers are now arguing about who will control the existing business - from which, according to Paul, Colin excluded him.
Colin argues that this is not the case, but accuses Paul of incompetent management of some facilities.
In testimony given by Colin at the beginning of the trial, he says he hopes to resolve the dispute.
“My Italian roots make me consider family a top priority,” he wrote.
Court costs are growing like a snowball: hundreds of pages of testimony, emails, and reports from companies like Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, and Charter Keck Cramer are involved in the case; both parties have attracted some of the best-known lawyers, including royal lawyer Allan Myers, and top-of-the-line suitors.
Mrs. De Lutis and her late husband, Luigi, were immigrants from Italy; from the late 1950s they ran dairy bars and gourmets, and in the early 1970s they bought a store in Brunswick.
Under financial guarantees, they bought a store in Collingwood, in which Colin opened the first family store of jeans.
Colin says he started Westco when he was “in the last grades of school and Paul was a boy (about 10 years old) at the time.”
Anna De Lutis says she and Luigi, who died in 2012, had hoped to hand over their possessions to their sons without conflict.
“Luigi has often told me that he doesn’t want the brothers to go to court,” she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutys group of companies; Colin says that Mark received 10 million when he left the business, and Luke 26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark were “dissatisfied with the financial conditions of their branch.”
Colin was not a public figure, although he was a former member of the board of directors of the AFL club and, according to a 2015 biography of Eddie McGuire, the best friend of the TV star.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
Colin replied only with a text message, which said that since the case had not yet been heard in court, "I really have nothing much to say."
“I am very, very sorry that my brother Paul has decided to file a lawsuit against me and bring our family’s name to justice,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a statement that he was trying to satisfy his brother’s demands.
“Our father wouldn’t want to see Paul and I argue in court,” he said, adding that he was still “hoping for a resolution of the conflict.”
On Friday, that hope seems to have dissipated.
“A decision on our case will be made soon by the court,” Colin wrote.
The new head of the Trump administration plans to limit the flow of information to the president.
Others tried to do so and were defeated.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it.
In that case, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to limit the flow of information coming to President Trump, including news reports from the media - hoping to keep the chief in a calmer state.
That's what reporter Josh Dowsey reports.
“At a meeting that the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, held with the White House leadership on his first day, he outlined a major problem in the White House under President Donald Trump that he hopes to solve: bad channels of information to the president.”
Kelly told staff that the information should go through him — in paper form or through briefings — because the president would be better off making decisions if he was getting the right information.
Kelly’s diagnosis is perfectly correct, but others have already failed in trying to pacify Trump by tracking the flow of information to him.
President Trump’s relationship with television began decades ago — and now that he’s in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still strong.
“When Trump, as a candidate, resented the unfair coverage of the campaign, it was helpful to demonstrate to him that he was getting fair coverage in publications that could be reconfirmed,” Sam Nanberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Tara Palmeri wrote in Politico that “in the words of six former campaign staff members, in order to keep Trump’s Twitter habit under control, it was necessary to ensure that there was a constant stream of praise in the information coming to him personally.”
Oh, good.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter habit has ever been “under control” is ludicrous.
Maybe these campaign members know something we don’t, like that if it wasn’t for them, Trump’s tweets would have been even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets that Trump didn’t post.
If his employees saved him from trouble at least several times, their efforts were not in vain.
But no one has ever been able to keep Trump from pouring oil on the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by handing Trump material — reliable or not — that confirms their views.
Politico - just to this story - wrote in May about the tendency of advisers to constantly give the president dubious information.
Here is an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
“Trump’s current and former staffers say Trump can react very harshly to negative press reports, especially containing dangerous leaks, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
That happened in late February, when someone planted a printout of an article from GotNews.com, the website of Internet provocateur Charles K. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Welsh was accused of being “stands for a number of leaks” in the White House.
It doesn’t matter that Johnson is forever banned on Twitter for aggressive behavior, that he hasn’t presented specific facts, or that in the past he has launched false accusations and then dropped them.
Trump read the article and began to ask employees about Welsh.
Goldmacher adds that then Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and Staff Secretary Rob Porter “tried to build a system to manage and document the flow of papers that Trump receives.”
How'd that work?
Three months later, Kelly tries to do the same.
He may prove to be a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his aides are still fighting each other for influence.
These constant factors make Kelly’s task very difficult.
Tyumen Prosecutor's Office fights HIV-dissident
The prosecutor’s office challenged the decision of the Kalinin district court of Tyumen, which terminated the criminal case against a local resident whose young daughter died of HIV.
According to the investigation, the child died due to the fact that the mother is an HIV dissident and refused treatment.
However, the court absolved her of responsibility in connection with the reconciliation with the injured father.
The prosecutor’s office believes that the crime cannot be left unpunished, so as not to set a precedent for other HIV-dissidents.
The case against a resident of Tyumen was initiated under Part 1 of Article 109 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (causing death by negligence) in April - after her three-year-old daughter died of HIV infection stage 4B.
According to the prosecutor's office, the mother herself is HIV-positive.
"The woman did not treat herself and refused to treat her daughter, believing that HIV infection does not exist," the prosecutor's office of the Tyumen region explained.
The criminal case was submitted to the Kalininsky District Court of Tyumen, which on July 25 decided to terminate it.
The petition was filed by the father of the deceased girl, explaining that "I have forgiven my wife, has no complaints to her, she made amends and apologized."
The prosecutor's office disagreed with the court's decision and appealed, demanding that the decision to dismiss the case be overturned and sent for reconsideration.
The girl died, and it is impossible to make amends for the harm caused by the crime.
The HIV-infected mother, contrary to the recommendations of doctors, refused to examine the baby and treat it for a dangerous infection," the press service of the prosecutor's office said.
According to the supervisory authority, she should be punished, otherwise her example will be followed by other HIV-dissidents.
As told in the Tyumen AIDS Center, now in the Tyumen region about 12 children with HIV do not receive medical care because of the refusal of parents.
"And this situation has already improved - during the year of the work of the special group, half of the parents who categorically refused to treat children with HIV changed their opinion - they allowed to diagnose, began to take drugs," said Elena Loseva, a spokeswoman for the AIDS Center.
According to her, it is impossible to influence parents in a legislative way, and as a result, not all HIV-infected children can be detected - mothers do not allow them to be examined, hide, run away with children from hospitals.
The Dangers of HIV Dissidents
At the end of last year, St. Petersburg sociologists presented the results of the first study in Russia of the so-called movement of HIV-dissidents.
HIV-dissidents are people who deny the existence of HIV and refuse to take medication.
Doctors and activists of AIDS-service NGOs call such views anti-medical, and in their dissemination they see a serious threat.
