Gypsies overcame the moat and returned to the “street of millionaires”
Some of West Midland’s wealthiest homeowners are once again in conflict with the determined Roma who have overcome a moat dug by municipal authorities to retake the field near their homes.
The gypsies parked 20 houses on wheels in a field bordering the rich Solihalla street, which was jokingly called the “street of millionaires”.
Bringing with them horses, infants, and a host of houses on wheels, they returned after they had been driven out no further than in May, and were not hindered by a moat dug by the municipal authorities to prevent their invasions.
This tactical company found a gap in the defensive structures and pushed their vehicles through the section, which was left unfenced to leave room for the path.
Angry residents attacked the municipality of Solihull, saying it had been "unable to solve this problem".
An anonymous local resident said: “They came here on Monday evening after being driven out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passers-by.”
The municipality should be shamed and forced to act, because they are completely incapable of solving this problem.
The gypsies were here in May, they were banished, and here they are again.
Last night, more gypsies came, and today, perhaps, more.
“Birmingham Municipality knows how to solve this problem, they get long-term court orders to protect their parks,” she added.
I live on Streetsbrook Road, and I don’t like that I keep paying the municipal tax, and the municipality can’t even put an end to it.”
One local resident, who wished to remain anonymous, said: “It’s funny, we just saw these gypsies leave the last time, and here, please, this attack continues.”
This time there were more of them, and we even saw a horse grazing in the meadow.”
A Solihull municipality spokesman said: “We are aware of an illegal camp on the ground near Streetsbrook Road and are cooperating with Solihull police; we are taking the necessary legal action to drive them out as soon as possible.”
To assist us in the collection of evidence, it is very important that as many local residents as possible report any antisocial or criminal behavior to the police by calling 101.
This allows us to form an idea of the situation that the court will consider when we present our case to them.
Crimea shares the factory of champagne wines "Novy Svet"
The SUE of the Republic of Crimea "Champagne Wine Plant "Novy Svet" decided to share, transforming into OJSC "Champagne Wine Plant "Novy Svet", follows from the order of the Minister of Property and Land Relations of Crimea Anna Anyukhina.
100% of the shares of the enterprise will remain in the state ownership of the Crimea.
The authorized capital of the joint-stock company will be 595,5 million rubles and will consist of 5,955 million ordinary shares with a nominal value of 100 rubles each.
The Ministry of Agriculture of the Crimea stated that if within the next three years there are no funds for the modernization of the enterprise, then there will be a threat of stopping the plant.
The depreciation of fixed assets in the enterprise is about 60-70%.
For the modernization of the enterprise, 1.2 billion rubles are needed. Due to the peculiarities of the organizational and legal form, it is obliged to give 50% of the profit to the budget income.
What remains is not enough to implement the modernization plan.
"It is problematic to get money from the owner, it is difficult to talk about attracting borrowed funds from large credit institutions," Deputy Head of the Ministry of Agriculture of Crimea Sergey Petelin said in April this year.
The Crimean Parliament included the enterprise in the forecast privatization plan for 2017.
It was proposed to carry out its shareholding and put up for auction.
A source of "Interfax" in the authorities of the Crimea estimated the possible cost of the sale of the enterprise at $ 40 million, the investor's investment in modernization - another $ 30 million.
“New World” in 2016 increased the production of sparkling wines by 2.8% compared to the level of 2015 – up to 1.52 million bottles.
In 2017, Novy Svet planned to produce 1.6 million bottles.
The company was founded in 1878 by Prince Lev Golitsyn as a factory for the production of sparkling wine in the New World estate he acquired.
The plant is located on 11 hectares of land.
