Italy is tightening its tone with regard to NGO ships rescuing migrants.
Italy has warned the NGOs that own rescue vessels in the Mediterranean Sea that they will not be able to continue their work unless they comply with the new rules governing their activities.
“If NGOs do not comply with the new code of conduct, it is difficult to say whether they will be able to continue their activities,” Interior Minister Mario Minniti told the Turin daily Stampa.
Minniti’s warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rettet on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with human traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has only worked for a year, declined to comment on the merits of the detailed charges brought against it by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
“For us, saving human life is and will remain a top priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot now continue to operate in the search and rescue zone,” the organization said in a statement on social media.
“We will only be able to assess all the allegations made now after we have gathered all the information and will be able to assess the situation.”
Italian authorities have been monitoring the Juventa vessel, owned by Jugend Rettet, since October.
Its crew is suspected of taking on board migrants with whole lifeboats, which human traffickers sent directly to them, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting is believed to have taken place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the indictment, which was published in Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coastal authorities, who control rescue operations in the area, more out of humanitarian zeal than for any other motives.
The Code of Conduct assumes mainly that Juventa vessels will have an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the code: Save the Children, the Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday it considered the new rules unnecessary but acceptable provided they did not entail any “significant changes or disruption” to its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
Minniti, meanwhile, said the sharp decline in recent weeks in the number of migrants arriving in Italy as a result of rescue operations indicates that efforts to support the Libyan coastguard and co-operate with local mayors are bearing fruit.
“In recent days, we have begun to see the light at the end of the tunnel,” he said.
He announced plans for further negotiations with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
“In Libya, we don’t want to be associated with either side of the conflict.
The Russian authorities have recently significantly intensified their policy in the Libyan direction, and delegations of the warring Libyan parties have frequented their visits to Moscow.
The head of the Russian contact group on the intra-Libyan settlement at the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Russian Federation and the State Duma, assistant to the head of the Chechen Republic Lev Dengov told Kommersant what goals Moscow pursues in this region and on whom it bets.
Almost nothing is known about the Libya contact group you are leading.
Here, for example, the contact group on Ukraine - everyone knows about it.
And here's the veil of secrecy.
What exactly do you do, what goals do you pursue?
The contact group was established at the initiative of the Russian Foreign Ministry and the State Duma.
Its activities are supervised by the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Mikhail Bogdanov and Adam Delimkhanov (deputy of the Duma from Chechnya - "Kommersant").
The latter is authorized to work in the Libyan direction by the speaker of the state Duma Vyacheslav Volodin.
The impetus for the creation of the group was the detention in Libya of the Russian tanker "Mekhanik Chebotarev" (in September 2015, there were 11 people on board. - "Kommersant").
We thought about how to help the crew.
Then a contact group of military specialists, representatives of the State Duma, was created, our work was supported by the head of Chechnya, Ramzan Kadyrov.
And how did it happen that you were the one who led it?
Since I have been working on Libya since 2008, I have been asked to lead the work of the group.
Our activity was not limited to the release of sailors from the Chebotarev Mechanics.
We have been able to establish contacts with representatives of all major groups opposing each other in the Libyan conflict - both from Tripoli (where the UN-recognized government headed by Faiz Sarraj is based. - "Kommersant"), and from Tobruk (the residence of the parliament that opposes the government and supports Marshal Khalifa Haftar, who controls the eastern regions of Libya. ".
Thanks to the active participation of Ahmed Metig (Vice Prime Minister of Libya - "Kommersant"), we were able to quickly agree on the release of Russian sailors.
Then it was decided to use these contacts more effectively, to create a contact group.
Its task is to analyze the situation, identify key factors and players, dialogue with all parties to the conflict.
I want to emphasize that in Libya we do not want to be associated with either side of the conflict, we are in dialogue with all.
How many people are in the contact group and how many are permanently in Libya?
There are currently five people in the contact group.
Among them there are people with experience in law enforcement agencies, including the Ministry of Defense.
We also want to include a group of specialists on the region, representatives of the Institute of the Middle East of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
None of our employees are constantly in Libya, this is not necessary yet.
Are there now Russian military advisers, instructors in Libya?
And if so, on whose side?
There are no Russian military specialists in Libya.
All the talk and publications about this are not true.
But your contact group includes former military personnel...
Yes, and their presence is necessary.
For example, when we visit hot spots.
Or cities closed to us until a certain point, such as Misrata (where militias are based, which played a role in the overthrow of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi in 2011 and significantly intensified in subsequent years. - "Kommersant").
We arrived in Misrata in January of this year.
We were scared, they said that there were Islamists, terrorists.
But it was important for us to assess the situation there ourselves, to analyze the real military potential, who is responsible for what, why there are such rumors, what is the real role of Islamists there.
In Misrata, we met with all the representatives of the detachments that were engaged in the destruction of ISIS in Sirte (in December 2016, this city on the Mediterranean coast was recaptured from the militants of the Islamic State banned in Russia - "Kommersant").
We wanted to look at them, to meet these people, to check the information that they played a decisive role in the destruction of ISIS in Libya, and not Khalifa Haftar, who attributed these merits to himself.
And what conclusion have you reached?
Did the Islamic State defeat Haftar in Libya?
He didn't do it.
Haftar conducted operations on the other front, in Benghazi.
And with ISIS in Sirte fought the structures that were subordinate to the government in Tripoli.
And, by the way, we invited to Russia people who conducted this anti-terrorist operation.
And they arrived - the visit lasted from 19 to 23 April this year, the Libyan delegation was received in the Federation Council, in the Duma, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Regardie.
You, as we understand, are in all Libyan regions and probably imagine the moods of local elites and field commanders.
Do you think it will be possible to implement the ceasefire agreement on holding the elections that Khalifa Haftar and Faiz Sarraj reached in Paris at the end of July?
Or again, as has happened many times in the past, will agreements be broken, fighting resume, the parties will try to seize power alone?
For us, a good signal was the fact that Sarraj and Haftar agreed to another meeting, not so long ago it was impossible.
In the recent past, both leaders have been extremely negative about each other.
As for Russia's position...
They often write and say that Moscow actively supports Haftar, many believe it.
We faced this situation when we were in Misrata, and it was on this day that Haftar climbed aboard the Russian aircraft carrier Admiral Kuznetsov.
It was a coincidence.
But Misrata did not believe in coincidence.
We were told, “You must be very brave people to come to us today.”
But our task is precisely to show that we do not only support Haftar, we are in dialogue with all the key actors in the conflict in Libya.
You and Haftar have spoken.
Does understanding with Russian partners on a human, emotional level make it easier for him to study in the USSR twice?
And, by the way, does Haftar know Russian?
He is Russian, if he knows it, it is very relative.
But the fact that he studied with us, of course, facilitates the dialogue with him.
Not just with him, by the way.
When we communicate with the military in Tripoli and Misrata, we meet generals who studied either in Russia or in the Soviet Union.
And they speak Russian very well.
And they are drawn to Russia, to some extent they feel nostalgia for it.
Do you consider it likely that the arms embargo on Libya will be lifted soon?
Are your Libyan interlocutors interested in the supply of Russian weapons?
They are interested, of course, but, as I have already said, we do not take sides in this conflict and do not want to arm some at the expense of others.
We want everyone to be in roughly equal positions.
As for the arms embargo, Libyans are constantly calling for Russia to somehow facilitate its lifting.
The process of drafting a constitution is now being actively promoted in Libya.
We hope that the parties will reach compromise solutions, achieve an internal consensus.
Then the elections should take place, which was also discussed at the meeting of Saraj and Haftar.
If the elections are held and the legitimate government is finally elected (and neither side has such status now), then it is possible to raise the issue of lifting the arms embargo in the UN Security Council.
Raising this issue now is pointless and dangerous, it will only lead to an escalation of the conflict.
Recently, the media reported that Italy, faced with the problem of African refugees sailing from Libya, feels abandoned by EU allies.
Can Moscow help Italian partners in this situation by using its ties with the Libyans?
How realistic is it, for example, that Haftar’s troops will establish control over the coast and put an end to the business of smugglers transporting immigrants to Europe?
A very timely question.
We are actively working on it.
The Italians need Russia’s support because Moscow is in dialogue with both Haftar and Sarraj, Misurata and the south of the country.
And in this matter, the tribes in southern Libya play a big role, and they are ready to cooperate with Russia.
Is it about the fact that the southerners cut off the flow of migrants on distant approaches?
That is, conditionally speaking, they turned back the buses in which Nigerian migrants go?
That's what we're trying to do.
But it's not easy.
Some clans and groups are interested in keeping these flows going.
We hope to help bring the South together in the negotiation process between Sarraj, Haftar and the tribes in the south.
But first, we would like to see the unity of opinion on this issue between Haftar and Sarraj.
The head of the government in Tripoli, Faiz Sarraj, is considered an Islamist, a supporter of the introduction of Sharia norms in the country.
How radical is he?
Will this be an obstacle to building relations with Russia or the West?
I will give my personal opinion of him.
In my opinion, he is, on the contrary, an opponent of radical Islam.
But the Islamists are in his coalition.
Yes, but he himself holds the position that Libya should be an absolutely normal country - moderately Islamic, open to the world.
They are also actively fighting terrorists.
Where did he get such a reputation?
It was created by those countries that are not interested in Russia communicating with Tripoli.
Tripoli is the capital, where the legislative, executive and judicial powers are located.
There is a national oil corporation, a national bank and other state structures.
Of course, some countries were interested in us not climbing there.
And we mixed all the cards for them and began to actively communicate with Tripoli and Tobruk.
And we are already reaping the fruits of this work: Rosneft has concluded a cooperation agreement with the state oil company of Libya - NOC.
NOC Director Mustafa Sanalla, with whom the head of Rosneft Igor Sechin concluded a deal, himself directly from Tripoli.
And two weeks ago, the first shipment of Libyan oil to Rosneft took place.
What will Russia do with it?
I think it's oversold.
What are Russia’s economic interests in Libya?
It is planned to re-sign the contracts concluded under Muammar Gaddafi.
These include, in particular, the previous agreements in the transport sector (construction of railways), energy (electrification) and a number of others.
Do Libyans have anything to pay?
Well, they have oil.
That is, as in the case of Iran, is it about the scheme "oil in exchange for services"?
I do not know what the scheme will be, I do not deal with these issues directly.
In fact, the economy for Russia in Libya is not the main thing.
We are essentially doing peacekeeping work there.
The main thing for us is to stop the bloodshed, to help the Libyans to come to an agreement among themselves so that they can establish order and Libya will cease to be a favorable environment for the development of terrorism.
For Russia, this is the main task - to help the Libyan people and to drive out the terrorists.
Do you have data on the presence in Libya (now or before) of radical militants from Russia or other countries of the former USSR?
One of the tasks of our contact group was to clarify this.
I met with a representative of the Libyan State Security Committee, who said that to date, no natives of Russia and other countries of the former USSR are there.
He said he had about 50,000 recordings of phone calls from Islamist and radical groups in Libya, and that there was no Russian language there.
Which countries are these fighters from?
I don’t want to go into those details.
Let’s formulate the question differently.
How many are the Libyans themselves among the Islamist militants in Libya?
There are almost no Libyans among them, they are no more than 5%.
The rest are newcomers.
Can Moscow hold intra-Libyan talks on the example of Paris?
There are such plans.
We are actively negotiating with the Libyans, several delegations from Libya have already visited Moscow, and declared their readiness to come to Moscow or Grozny.
When can such negotiations take place?
It's hard to tell now.
There are still several visits to be made, and then, I hope, there will be clarity about the time and place of negotiations.
