Michelle Carter Sentenced for Reporting on Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two-and-a-half years in prison for using text messages and phone calls to induce the suicide of her boyfriend Conrad Roy.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will have to serve 15 months behind bars and another five years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father said at Thursday’s hearing: “My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was allowed to remain at large until his appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said she and Roy both suffered from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the verdict standing, clutching her hands and lowering her eyes.
“By her actions, she killed Conrad Roy,” the prosecutor told the court.
“She interrupted his life to improve hers.
“She did not accept responsibility,” she said.
"She showed no remorse."
But Carter’s lawyer said it was a “tragic case that she deeply regrets.”
However, Judge Lawrence Monis said that, in his opinion, her "age, level of maturity or even mental illness did not significantly affect her actions."
The prosecutor read out a statement from Roy’s mother Lynn Roy, which said: “Not a single day has gone by that I have not mourned the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it – I try to support his sisters, despite all the pain that will stay with us forever.”
Roy’s sister Camden Roy said she was haunted by the thought that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become the aunt of his children.
“Losing the person who has been with me since I was born is a pain that will stay with me for the rest of my life,” she said.
The case is likely to set a legal precedent, as there is no law in Massachusetts that would provide responsibility for advising a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in his car with symptoms of carbon monoxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The incident caught the attention of the whole country when it became known that he was pushed to suicide by Carter's messages.
“You can hang yourself, jump off a roof, stab yourself with a knife I don’t know there are many ways,” she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, while he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad," and "You just have to turn on the light, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monis said that Carter wanted to get attention with Roy's death, and forbade her to communicate with the press to prevent her from getting what she wanted.
The views of the lawyers on this matter are divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 of murdering her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
The 30-year-old Knox published a separate opinion in the Los Angeles Times, which stated: “Michelle Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison.”
