The murder of a journalist underscores that Mexico is becoming increasingly dangerous.
Employees of the Riodose weekly newspaper usually meet on Wednesdays to discuss plans to cover the latest violent crimes in Sinaloa state involving organized crime, corrupt officials or the ongoing drug war.
But today, overwhelmed by their own tragedy, they met to talk about security.
They were told that they had to change their habits.
The two senior journalists discussed what seemed safer: taking the children with them to an office where a grenade had already been thrown in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts wrote three words on the board hanging in the room: enemies, neutral people, allies.
They asked journalists to name names for each column - no evidence is needed, suspicions and internal feelings will be enough.
These are drug dealers, politicians, businessmen, journalists who are suspected of being held by the government or the cartels, a whole list of scoundrels who make the work of covering the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
Violence is on the rise, and there are more and more journalists among the corpses that are multiplying in the country: according to the Committee to Protect Journalists, at least 25 since President Enrico Pena Nieto took office in December 2012; 589 people are under federal protection after attacks and threats; and this year at least seven people have died in seven states.
Among the latter is their publisher and inspirer, co-founder of Riodose Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is to live in Mexico and be a journalist,” Valdés wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violent crimes.
His absence is felt very acutely, although his presence is ubiquitous – a large photograph of Valdez showing his middle finger, with the inscription “Justice” hanging on the facade of the Riodose building; two reporters in their 30s, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wearing T-shirts that depict his firmament or face.
The seminar takes place less than two months after his death; journalists discuss their general trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to investigate journalistic cases, so far only two cases have been investigated, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of drug and organized crime-related murders committed each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
Riodoza journalists insist they will write about the violence in Sinaloa, although they are heartbroken, although around now much more dangerous.
Without information about the killers, without justice from talking about safety at meetings, there is little benefit, says Ibarra.
“It’s very silly to waste time at this seminar,” he says.
“Until we know the cause, we suspect everyone.”
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left Riodose’s office in the state capital of Culiacan.
He managed to drive only a couple of blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men; he was pulled out of the car and shot 12 times, probably because of the name of the newspaper – which means “Twelfth River”.
The shooter drove away in his car and smashed it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He has a wife and two adult children.
Rumors usually spread quickly around Kuliakan.
But almost everyone is silent about Valdes.
Since Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S. last January, Sinaloa has become one of the bloodiest battlegrounds in the country as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
Let’s not talk about the fact that one or more people are killed every day on the streets of Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is filled with decorated two-story mausoleums of drug kings, which are larger than the homes of many living people.
Let’s forget for a moment that the state of “calm” is simply when one of the cartels takes control of a coastal state with important ports and drug trafficking routes leading to the United States.
Despite the fact that Valdez was well aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bohorquez, the 60-year-old co-founder and director of Riodose, is crushed by guilt for failing to protect a friend.
He thinks the murder was helped by two mistakes.
First, in February, an interview was published with Damaso Lopez, the leader of one of the rival factions of the cartel, which is at war with the sons of Guzman.
The publication may have angered the sons; the people who were supposed to be members of the gang bought all copies of the publication as soon as they were delivered to the kiosks.
The second mistake was that he did not force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after another newspaper that wrote about the same story was captured.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his murder was seen as another milestone in the development of violence against journalists in Mexico.
He had been out of danger for so long, his friends and colleagues thought he would always be.
He was an experienced reporter at Noroest, and in 2003, along with five colleagues, he founded Riodos, selling his $50 stock.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to do journalism without dealing with drugs,” Bohorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation as a bold and honest publication, sales and advertising revenues grew.
Journalists liked that they could publish bold reports without fear of censorship, and readers were attracted to the fact that in this publication they could read about what no one else dared to write about.
Eight years after its founding, Riodose received the prestigious Maria Morse Cabo Award for her reporting work in Latin America.
That same year, Valdés won the International Press Freedom Prize for his courage in investigating Mexico’s drug trafficking, wherever it led.
He openly admitted that he was scared.
"I want to live on," he said at the CPJ award ceremony.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa is “a way of life,” he said last October in an interview with Rompevianto TV.
“You have to accept the tasks that fall on you as a journalist – either that or you’re just fooling around.”
I don't want to be asked, "What were you doing when there were so many deaths... why didn't you tell me what was going on?"
Riodos staff miss Valdez, a joker who scolded like a port loader, a friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They relied on the order they were in.
He always had to wear his hat.
He had to go to El Guayabo, the bar opposite the office, and always sit there at the same table.
Now they ask: did he lose his love for the once-established order?
His death also made them question their calculations of how best to do their job and stay alive.
“They don’t like it when you know their wives, their children, their legitimate business, and their underground drug-carrying airfields.
“These things were behind the line,” Bohorquez said.
The result, even in the best of times, was a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
You have to trust your instincts.
Stay away from anything that smells bad.
The problem, says Riodose editor Andrés Villarreal, is that “the infatuation can be fooled... and then what happened to Javier happens.”
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa — as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero, and other states, where there is a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak government institutions, and corrupt officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodos employees gathered for security training, suddenly it was forbidden to bring cell phones: a few days before it became known that spy programs that are sold exclusively to governments are used in Mexico to spy on journalists and public activists.
Outside, two police officers are sheltering in the shade of a tree from 104 degrees of heat (40 degrees Celsius).
They were tasked by the state government to guard the Riodos office, which is located in a four-story building in the bourgeois quarter of Culiacan.
Some journalists half-jokingly asked if these police officers were among the 50 percent of law enforcement officers that the governor himself said they could not be trusted.
A few months ago, journalists went to a mountainous area that is de facto controlled by drug gangs.
In the next issue of "Riodos" counted on three main topics.
This is the murder in Sinaloa of the brother of former boxing champion Julio Cesar Chávez.
They also had exposure of government spending concentrated in the governor’s hometown.
And there was a group kidnapping at one of Culiacan's most expensive restaurants, a block from the D.A.'s office.
