“We would have known what happened before,” said Villareal, 46, nicknamed “El Flaco” for his lean physique.
"Today, all communication channels with our sources have been severed."
Valdez’s office is now used as a warehouse for posters and stickers protesting the killings of journalists, because employees have become what they never thought they would become: activists speaking on behalf of the press.
Journalist Miriam Ramirez took several posters and went the next morning to a demonstration at the local prosecutor's office dedicated to another journalist.
El Salvador Adame disappeared in the western state of Michoacan three days after Valdez was killed.
They found the burned body, and authorities said it was him, based on DNA tests.
Across the country, journalists began to speak up, organize protests and write “SOS Press” on the sidewalks and walls of houses.
On that day, Director Bohorquez was in Washington, D.C., trying to enlist international support in demanding justice in the Valdez case.
At a meeting with Sinaloa’s governor the day after Valdés’ murder, Ram<0xC3><0xAD>rez accused authorities of spying on journalists and ordering them to be killed for telling the truth.
After that, she asked not to give her more tasks to cover the activities of the government, fearing that anger would damage her objectivity.
Valdés has said many times that journalists in Mexico are “surrounded” by organized crime, its accomplices in government, and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Drug Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not just killed by gangs of drug traffickers; they are killed by politicians and security services colluded with organized crime.
The Article 19 Press Protection Committee believes that half of the attacks on journalists last year were carried out on the orders of police and government officials.
“In Mexico, you die because they want to shut you up,” Ramirez says.
Of course, killing scares people.
Everyone remembers the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
On her body was found a note supposedly written on behalf of the Zetas cartel: "I'm here because of my articles."
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some newspapers chose to close like the El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after its correspondent Miroslava Brich was killed in March.
Others continue to hold out like El Manyana from Nuevo Laredo after its leader was assassinated in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juárez publicly addressed the drug cartels through an editorial on the front page entitled “What do you want from us?”
Some journalists have left their home states or the country in general.
This is a painful decision.
In exile, it is difficult to find work, and they continue to look for danger on the streets.
And sometimes they are killed, as apparently happened with photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was killed in 2015 along with four women in an apartment in Mexico three months after fleeing Veracruz.
Those who stay and continue to work, daily balance between risky decisions.
Ibarra — who once dreamed of being a poet — admits he’s scared to write about the drug trade.
“Mexico is going to hell, and that’s why I became a journalist,” he says.
Last Friday, at midnight, when the latest issue was ready for print, Riodos publishers were sitting on the sidewalk near the office drinking beer when their phones rang simultaneously.
A series of shootings between rival gangs and security forces near the resort city of Masatlan left behind, according to confirmed reports, 19 corpses.
The war continued to flare up, as promised in a series of messages from cartels discovered in the area.
Sitting on the sidewalk, they posted the news on the Riodos website via their mobile phone.
The next day I had to re-write the first page.
There were sirens in the vicinity - another firefight in the vicinity.
Bohorkes looked to see if the policemen guarding them were ready to defend themselves.
If they were scared, they didn’t show it.
Sitting under a huge portrait of the deceased founder of their newspaper, whose middle finger was exposed to the whole of Sinaloa, Riodos employees continued his work.
"How can you think of closing," Bohorquez said, "if on the very day Javier was killed, an intern asked me to send her out to report?"
The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
The researchers said that the first remains of an incredible rhino-sized creature found by a Canadian miner were so well preserved that experts called it the “Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.”
It was so well preserved that they were even able to determine that the color of his scaly skin was reddish-brown—and to say that he had, in some way, a “dark past.”
In a report published in the journal Modern Biology, it was described as “the best-preserved of the Thyrophorus in the history of the finds and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
This fossil is a newly found specimen of a nodosaur that lived in the middle of the Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredible good condition has stunned researchers who call it “really remarkable.”
This herbivorous thyrophorus is the best-preserved fossil of its kind in the history of the finds, according to articles in the National Geographic journal.
It was found by Sean Funk while he was working at Sankor's Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
He came across something that seemed different from the surrounding breed, and decided to look more closely.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
For the next six years, work was carried out to find an animal inside an earthen block weighing 2,500 feet (1,100 kilograms).
Now that all this hard work is done, the finished result can be demonstrated.
“It only takes a little squinting, and you can almost believe he’s asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a research fellow at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum, which showcases the creation.
He will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved specimens of dinosaurs – the Mona Lisa among dinosaurs.
Studying its skin, the researchers found that it was herbivorous, despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank, apparently exposed to significant danger from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This powerfully shelled dinosaur used red-and-white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as protective coloring, which is also used by many animals today.
This would allow it to merge more quickly with the environment and avoid encountering enemies, experts say, suggesting that larger dinosaurs hunted it.
This 110-million-year-old creature, belonging to the nodosaur family, was widely covered in print in May, and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Paleontological Museum.
Scientists have already studied the animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli in honor of museum laboratory assistant Mark Mitchell, one of the members of the group, who spent more than 7,000 hours behind his painstaking excavation.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr. Mitchell and an international group of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor plates on his body.
They found a protective coloration, a common method of protection in the animal kingdom, which means that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although the protective coloration is well-spread, the discovery came as a surprise because the size of the Borealopelta dinosaur is significantly larger than the size of living animals with protective coloration.
It can be assumed that this dinosaur was so actively hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred to mask confrontation as a way of survival.
But most modern animals with a protective coloring - for example, deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and are more affordable prey, which indicates that nodosaurs had to seriously fight for survival.
“The serious threat posed by predators to a massive, heavily shelled dinosaur shows just how dangerous the predatory dinosaurs of the Cretaceous period were,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in the dinosaur scales also suggests that its skin was supposed to be reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal, looking for information about its life, including the preserved contents of its digestive tract, to find out what it ate during its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it fell into the river and was carried away into the sea, where it sank and with its back went down to the bottom of the ocean.
Back then, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and rivers and oceans likely extended much further inland than they do now.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin, and at the same time completely preserved in three dimensions, preserving the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
“As a result, the animal now looks almost the same as it did then, in the Early Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to recreate it, you just have to look a little bit more closely, and you can almost believe that he’s asleep.”
The Cretaceous period is the era when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs standing on two legs, roamed the Earth.
Although the most remarkable of these, the Tyrannosaurus rex, lived millions of years later than the Borealopelta, a thyrophore could have been hunted by one of its formidable ancestors.
These include the acrocanthosaur, a 38-foot (11.5 m) long monster weighing six tons.
Scientists, whose latest discoveries are published in the journal Modern Biology, believe that Borealopelta was taken to the sea after death and mummified in silt.
The creature was found by Sean Funk while he was working at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum staff, it is the best-preserved thyrophore in the world, along with skin and armor, and it is intact, from the snout to the femur.
On average, these creatures reached about 18 feet (five meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kilograms).
Their characteristic feature was two twenty-inch spikes protruding from the shoulders.
The researchers believe that this herbivorous thyrophorus was heavily treading on what is now Canada until a spilled river carried it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur’s underwater burial preserved its shell with precision down to the smallest detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates along the dinosaur skull.
As Michael Error wrote in an article for National Geographic magazine, such a degree of safety is “rare as winning the lottery.”
The longer I look at him, the more amazing he seems.
Fossilized remains of the skin still cover the bumpy shell plates, sowing the skull of the animal.
His right foreleg is extended along the side, five fingers on it are turned upwards.
I can count the scales on his sole.”
