How did one activist find out the answer to the question “Whose streets?”
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after arriving in New York as part of a tourist trip, a St. Louis native was sitting on a bed in an apartment rented through Airbnb, looking at a Facebook feed on her phone.
She ran into someone from high school.
It read: “Police have just killed an eighteen-year-old child and he is still lying in the middle of the street.”
Noting that no one else in her feed had posted this information, she was puzzled and closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
There were a lot of reposts in her feed with the name <0x40>TheePharoah.
A rapper from Greater St. Louis tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old boy killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He published a photograph of Brown’s lifeless body, spread out in the middle of the street, where it would remain for four hours.
“It’s wild,” Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her circle.
She put the phone down, and later in the evening came back to tweets that people were going to Canfield Drive.
There were pictures of a signal tape and screaming people and a man claiming to be Brown’s father holding up a poster saying, “A Ferguson police officer just killed my unarmed son!”
She watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another police officer, she said, pulled the trigger of a rifle and yelled, “I’m going to kill you all... animals!”
“It’s a non-standard situation,” Ferrell said at the time, according to her own recollections.
“This is not a murder like the ones we are used to and can call typical.
At that moment I felt a chill.
I was angry and crying.”
She took a return flight and flew home the next day.
Landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided that they would both go to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and resilience from the point of view of the people living in the community and filling the streets, demanding answers.
While Ferrell was driving to Ferguson with her daughter, dressed in a flower dress and a wreath of flowers, they recalled the conversation they had had up to this morning, countless times, "about the experience of black people and their situation."
She recalls saying, “Remember when I told you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?
We’re going to Ferguson now because an 18-year-old boy was killed by a police officer, and that was wrong.”
“I couldn’t help but take her,” Ferrell later said.
“What is happening today is the culmination of what has happened before.
She needs to know about it, see it, and be raised on it.
She must not only be well versed in activism and organization, but also understand the different levels of black experience and their situations, and what we must do to become free in order to be free.
Even if I manage to provide her with an environment in which she does not personally face obvious racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would do her a disservice if I fenced her off.”
When they arrived in Ferguson, they made their first stop at South Florissant Road, a site across the street from a police station that had become something of a tent camp, while activists waited for reports of Officer Darren Wilson’s final non-accusation.
There Ferrell and his daughter joined a local entrepreneur who prepared lunch packages.
They collected packages and helped distribute them to the protesters.
Little by little, Ferrell took the form of a new type of activism.
“My activism changed completely after August 9th,” she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Association of Health Students, National Minorities, and engaged in food justice and health inequalities among black communities.
“I had no experience as an organizer.
It came by itself.”
A few weeks later, at an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaa Folayan, one of her co-directors.
Folayan said she and her chief cameraman, Lucas Alvarado-Ferrar, "just wanted to document" the events.
Ferrell came up with the question: “Do you want to document, or are you trying to find a story to play?”
This skepticism was inspired by numerous people, often white, who came to the community to benefit from its pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, “We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson were not getting the spotlight, and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already teamed up with her co-director, Damon Davis, a local artist known for his activism on death row.
His involvement aroused sympathy for the project among Ferrell and six other locals, with whom the project's "Whose Streets?" team kept in touch during the years following Brown's murder.
“In this documentary, no one speaks for us or with us, we speak for ourselves,” Davis said.
“It was the most important thing for me how these people would be represented, because that’s how I would be represented myself.”
Although the goal of the project was not to focus on Ferrell’s experience at all – in an effort to show that the movement “is not about the leader-savior, but about how the community unites”, as Folayan said – it turned out to be the most open of the participants in the film.
As a result, Whose Streets? shows unexpectedly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love and married her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, laughing at how she first saw the finished product.
“But I realized that when you do that kind of work and you humanize black people, there has to be some level of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrell’s story again discusses and highlights the role of the black homosexual woman in the broader context of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement – those who created the #BlackLivesMatter tag on social media after the murder of black teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 – consider themselves homosexuals.
“Black gay women in leadership positions support this whole movement,” Ferrell says, “and that’s because we’re constantly fighting on several fronts.
Black gay women have to bear all this burden.”
Folayan agreed with this statement, noting that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a lot of gay black women."
However, she insists that "this is not a case of positive discrimination" and that Ferrell was not chosen as the film's central character because of her distinctive features.
“She was the one who awakened that energy,” she said.
"On the other hand, it's not a coincidence that she was in the foreground because when"
You can feel her energy through the screen.”
Ferguson, meanwhile, has long had no film cameras, but there remain complex racial ties between the community and the police.
Ferrell will be on probation for another two-and-a-half years for blocking the highway during a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the place, which she calls home, simply: “Bardak”.
She's still holding on to a line she learned when she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
We must fight for our freedom.
We have to win.
We must love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
