The emergence of similarities: the artist creates portraits using the DNA of Chelsea Manning
In the center of the hall at the Friedman Gallery in New York, the faces of people - white, black and brown - hang from the ceiling on a wire, all somewhat inconspicuously similar to each other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Harborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning has sent in incisions from Fort Leavenworth prison, where a former intelligence analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for famously relaying confidential diplomatic cables on the WikiLeaks website.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is called “The Emergence of Similarities”.
This is the result of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Harborg, whose art combines technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a transgender woman and a famous dissident, whom Barack Obama commuted just three days before the end of his presidency.
By analyzing Manning’s DNA from a computer program and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of faces that could be in people with such a genome, Dewey-Harborg created a deep, though not easy-to-perceive manifesto dedicated not only to the plasticity of DNA data – the different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinism of these interpretations – but also to the identity and identity of these interpretations.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has openly said since she was a teenager that she considers herself a woman, was sentenced in 2013 to 20 episodes, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her pictures in prison were unavailable, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black-and-white selfie, in which Manning, in a platinum shade of a wig, clearly feeling awkward, sits behind the wheel of a car; with this photo she became associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Harborg successfully completed her 2012 project Visions of Strangers.
In it, the artist created portraits of unknown people with the help of forensic evidence such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this garbage and creating images of what these people could look like.
And then she got an email from Paper Magazine.
“They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article,” Dewey-Hagborg explained at a preview of a new exhibition for the press.
Chelsea couldn’t be visited and photographed at the time, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted a portrait made of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters over the course of two years.
They even wrote a comic book, Repressed Images, illustrated by Shoila Kanungo, which depicted how in the future the president would commute Chelsea’s sentence and she would be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama actually decided to release Manning just days after the book was published was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There’s something deep and powerful about the exhibition opening right now, as Donald Trump declares war on people who reveal classified information in government, and invents new ways to incite on Twitter the enmity he’s designed to mitigate.
When Dewey-Harborg was asked about the coincidence of all this in time, she said that "accidentally nothing happens."
In a statement from the artist, written on the gallery wall, Manning’s huge signature at the bottom (with a heart instead of a dot over the “i” in her name) calls for an end to “automatic separation based on gender, race, sexual orientation and culture.”
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar of crayons C, G, and A.
Including 200 letters (or nucleotides, as the artist elegantly puts it in scientific terms), Dewey-Harborg hoped to show how amazingly similar we all are, at least in terms of our biological structure.
“I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open the genetic data is to interpretation, and how subjective it is,” Dewey-Harborg said.
“DNA data can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of those stories are here.”
The last part of the exposition, which fits in one room, is the above-mentioned novel in comics.
On it, Manning in the style of King Kong appears above the building of the Correctional Barracks of the United States with a loudspeaker in his hand.
“If they kill your speech, they will win,” it says.
"So never shut up."
“It’s a direct quote from a letter she wrote to me,” says the artist, greeting us from Philadelphia.
"I still have goose bumps when I talk about it."
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person – as it was prophetically portrayed in the comics – but when she arrives, she will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genomic simulacra gathering like a crowd of protesters.
This is also done intentionally, as well as all at the exhibition up to the height (5"2, Manning height), on which the genetic haplogroups were drawn with a pencil.
“I used to hang them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people,” Dewey-Harborg says of the portraits.
“I wanted them to be like the mass movement that formed around Chelsea, like the movement that was behind her liberation.”
