Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko: “We will fulfill the requirements of the WADA road map in the near future”
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said that the conditions of the World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA), set for the resumption of the work of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA), will be fulfilled in the near future.
“A certain stage in the implementation of the requirements has been passed, RUSADA received the right to plan and conduct tests together with UKAD (the anti-doping agency of Great Britain).
WADA’s road map has been updated accordingly,” Mutko said on Thursday.
The Prime Minister commented on the second part of WADA’s road map for restoring the status of compliance with the Code, which lists the conditions for the resumption of RUSADA’s work and was recently published on the organization’s website.
According to Mutko, it does not contain anything that could present difficulties for Russia.
“Everything has been announced, everything will be done.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future,” he added.
However, one of the requirements included in the list implies that Russian anti-doping agencies should publicly recognize the results of an investigation commissioned by WADA by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren, which claimed that doping in Russian sports is controlled by the state.
Mutko said: “We are investigating because our anti-doping system has failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs, and we will not recognize what did not happen.
Mutko echoed the words of Vitaly Smirnov, head of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In the morning of the same day, in an interview with the Russian edition of Rsport, Smirnov acknowledged previous problems in Russian anti-doping structures, but added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains certain controversial positions and provisions.
Unconditionally, no one is going to accept this report," Smirnov added.
WADA suspended RUSADA from doping control in November 2015 after a doping scandal.
