Startups that will help your company not to become another “Uber”
Amy Errett wanted to gauge the level of satisfaction among her e-commerce startup’s employees, but the surveys didn’t work.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, worse, insincere.
And even though she promised anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“He’s never been consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs San Francisco-based Madison Reed, a 75-person e-commerce hair care company.
She turned to third parties for help.
Now there is a new kind of startups in the field of work with staff, which help companies to find out how their employees feel.
By developing and licensing software designed to measure employee engagement, they allow companies to do express surveys, reach out to specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and hotlines for complaints, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass top management and contact management directly.
“We now have tools like Strava and Fitbit for health monitoring, but where is Fitbit for your company?” says Jim Barnett, co-founder and president of Redwood City-based startup Glint, whose analytics programs are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said that she has achieved a greater understanding of what her employees think and feel over the three years of using Glint.
In addition to express surveys and questionnaires of certain teams, the product offers a heat map of the company and shows in a visual form which departments have more complaints and which managers have a low approval rating, which allows it to understand why.
Companies are a little aware that they need to control the situation in the workplace, otherwise they will become another “Uber”, which was involved in the scandal, when the former employee published a blog post in which he described an aggressive environment in which those who expressed discontent were punished.
For startups like Glint, this desire to control the situation is an opportunity for a profitable business.
According to the Internet portal “Let’s talk about payment”, dedicated to financial technologies, the industry of global management, regulation and compliance by 2020 can cost more than $ 118.7 billion.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convertent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behavior, noted a slight increase in interest and activity earlier this year amid a decline in Uber’s reputation.
Convertent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Recently, Uber appeared among customers.
Like Glint, Convert allows companies to send custom-made staff opinion polls, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of problem areas.
It also provides a hotline for anonymous text messages that allows employees to report bad behavior.
And if the top manager is affected, the complaints go directly to the directorate.
“The court of public opinion has seized power from the inspectors,” said Patrick Quinlan, the founder and president of Convercent.
If it turns out that the company mistreats employees or behaves unethically, even if inspectors do not intervene, the company may face costly consequences in the form of boycotts by customers, employee outflows and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a chain of restaurants with more than 25,000 employees in 500 establishments, has used Convercent for more than a year to make sure employees are aware of the rules and procedures and offer an easy way to contact the company’s head office.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to look for a phone number or an email from the head office, file a formal complaint, and hope it was taken seriously.
It was often a frightening and embarrassing experience, said James Vitrano, head of the legal department at Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no normal way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convertent, problems that were previously hidden from managers sitting in offices in other cities or states – such as discrimination, harassment and unfair pay – can be detected and addressed more quickly.
“I can approach a holistic, comprehensive understanding of the situation of employees,” said Vitrano, who heads the risk management team at Ruby Tuesday.
“And we protect our shareholders from litigation with employees.”
According to Quinland, companies began to take ethics, values, and employee involvement more seriously in 2002, after accounting firm Arthur Andersen failed due to ethical violations as a result of the Enron Case.
But it wasn’t until “social media” became widespread that companies realized they couldn’t keep their dirty laundry from spreading virally online.
“Before starting to use technology to control ethics, people used hope as a strategy,” he said.
Both "Glint" and "Convercent" offer their software as a service, charging companies a regular fee for using their products.
This is a business model and opportunity that has received the approval of venture investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing the company’s total capital to $47 million.
Glint received $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing the company’s total capital to $60 million.
These investments are hardly surprising, given the interconnected nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research shows that today’s employees expect more from their jobs than ever before.
In markets with tough competition, such as Silicon Valley, high wages and interesting projects are just the bare minimum.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated, and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy working at a company, feeling heard, and that the work they do is delivering results, they’re more committed to making that company a success,” says Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee satisfaction at LinkedIn, where both Convert and Glint are used.
Investors make revenue when companies from their portfolios do well; companies do well when employees are loyal and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee loyalty and engagement, it’s no surprise that they find support.
According to experts on culture in the workplace, it is important to have data on employee involvement.
But the data is useless until the company's trustees take action.
In fact, if a company asks employees for feedback, it may give the impression that changes are coming.
And if change doesn’t happen fast enough, or doesn’t happen at all, frustration can develop and employees will lose interest.
“If you’re going to ask for 4,000 offers, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations,” says Russell Rath, president of consulting at management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because if you don’t go all the way, the staff will wonder, ‘Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don’t care, why shouldn’t I care?”
According to Errett, Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to take action the same day someone reports a problem with Glint.
And, after collecting feedback from employees dissatisfied with the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, she was able to reorganize several teams within the company and introduce communication training to solve problems.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining new knowledge about its employees and hopes that in the long run, this knowledge will help it to more effectively retain employees in an industry known for high staff turnover.
“If you don’t try to create a culture of transparency, you lose people,” Vitrano said.
If you lose people, you lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you lose companies.
