Create a novel-comic: One Castle in English History
In the recent past, the tiny castle of Scotty was filmed in the music video for "Squeeze", and in the 70s and 80s served as a haven for Margaret Thatcher.
But 700 years from his cozy place in the valley of the Buhl River in the county of Kent, he has watched the turbulent history around, and now inspired Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshireman with a head of hair and a penchant for historical documents, to a novel-comic.
“I think it’s so beautiful to look at the handwriting of a man who died 300 years ago,” he says.
"You feel it so personally when you hold this letter in your hand."
Castle in England covers the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian era and tells the story of the families who lived in Scotty; each story is illustrated by one of the young British artists - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
This isn’t Rhodes’ first book to be based on archival data: In 2014, he wrote Dead Man’s Teeth and Other Stories, a collection of documents from the British Library, a project that unexpectedly touched him to the core.
“I could have been touched simply by a fingerprint on the edge of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for the Jacobites,” he says.
"It's his fingerprint."
And letters always smell of smoke, because in those days for lighting lit a fire.
And 300 years from now, in the future, you think you're there, too.
Oh, how I love archives!
For a man with such a passion for old papers, getting support from the National Endowment and the English Arts Council and living in a castle for four months (“Honestly, I’ve been there a little bit”) seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days studying the "new" Victorian castle, going through the archives and examining the numerous treasures of the estate and ancient things - for example, the heads of hyenas on the walls or bottles that had lain in the pit for centuries.
He walked through the park and the ruins of the old castle, talking to foresters, gardeners, and sometimes artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he “drank whiskey and sat down to write.”
The history of the castle is not very studied, because the National Fund received full access to it only in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff was just beginning to deal with the archive, which he describes as “what aristocrats have been throwing at the attic for centuries.”
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing who owned what: “You think land disputes are boring,” says Rhodes, “but there were two families fighting over this birch.
It happens, guys!”
In some stories of the collection, the castle becomes the starting point for wider explorations in English history: for example, in The Worker, the hero leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasant Revolution of 1381.
“There is evidence of a rebellion that occurred at the castle in 1380, in a book called The Knights of Kent and Sussex,” says Rhodes.
"The Peasants' Revolt began in these places, and I thought the rebellion was a good start.
Maybe they were related?”
Other stories are strongly associated with the history of the castle - for example, "The Priest", which tells about the Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or “The Smuggler,” about 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who is believed to have staged his own funeral by stoning the coffin (this was discovered a few years later when the coffin was dug up).
The Durrells are the favorite family of Rods of all who inhabited Scotty: "Gentlemen seem to have been a perfect cheat, always getting into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, men-Darrell solved their problems with debt, marrying rich elderly women - I imagine them as a company of nice guys who know how to care for the heirs of large fortunes. "
After finishing his work at the castle, Rhodes looks for other opportunities to gain a unique writing experience.
He lived for two weeks in the Finnish wilderness, where he wrote a graphic novel about Elyamenm<0xC3><0xA4>ki - a place where at the beginning of the 20th century there was a sanatorium, and then it was overgrown with forest again.
But Scotty remains a special place for him.
“I was sad to leave,” he said.
“I felt like, ‘Damn, I have to go back to real life.’
