He decided to move to the position of Director for production coordination, - said at the enterprise. - Andrei Okhlopkov set before him the task to ensure the launch minimum for the first launch at the Vostochny cosmodrome fully fulfilled.
Mr. Okhlopkov moved to work at Tsenki in 2013, having served in space troops, in particular at Baikonur, and in Plesetsk - at the "northern" cosmodrome, he held the post of first deputy commander in the rank of colonel.
In 2009, Andrei Okhlopkov became a defendant in a criminal case.
The investigation accused him of bribery: allegedly, from his submission, regional merchants received state orders for kickbacks, but did not fulfill their obligations to clean up the separated parts of launch vehicles in the Arkhangelsk region and the Komi Republic.
In 2012, a jury found him not guilty.
The technological development responsibilities assigned to him by CENCI extended to various projects, but the main one was the construction of a spaceport in the Far East.
The then head of the Federal space Agency Oleg Ostapenko in an interview with "Kommersant" directly said that the situation in the East "was critical already in October 2013."
The fact is that during the planning, a strategic mistake was made: the completion of the construction and the first launch of the Soyuz-2.1 launch vehicle were planned for the same time - the end of 2015.
To carry out the launch before the end of the year, it was decided to complete the construction six months earlier and the deadlines were shifted from December to July 2015.
To speed up the process, it was necessary to go to the trick: the specialists of Tsenki began to conduct a parallel installation of technological equipment on unfinished objects.
The main supporter of this idea was Andrei Okhlopkov.
Despite the existing risks and the transfer that took place (instead of December 2015, the Soyuz departed only on April 28, 2016), this idea justified itself, the source of Kommersant at the spaceport says: “Otherwise we would not have carried out a single launch from the East, but would have been engaged in construction.”
Deputy Prime Minister Dmitry Rogozin, who oversees the creation of the spaceport, jokingly called Andrei Okhlopkov his “cosmic Susanin”, but it was from him that he almost always asked for information about the progress of construction.
Remember Mr. Okhlopkov and directness: for example, in an interview with Kommersant, he proposed to deprive the Federal Agency for Special Construction (Spetsstroy) of the status of the sole contractor for the East and directly work with subcontractors: "Why should we put all the eggs in one basket Spetsstroy?"
This idea has found support in the government.
Since 2017, Tsenki has taken over the duties of the general contractor in order to complete the construction and installation work on the launch and technical complex by the planned fourth quarter.
According to Kommersant, the reason for the transition of Mr. Okhlopkov to the new place of work were disagreements with the leadership of Tsenki regarding the ways to complete the construction of structures and complexes of the cosmodrome, as well as methods of work with subcontractors.
“It was decided that it would be better for everyone,” says one of the top managers involved in the construction of the East.
An employee of the government apparatus, in turn, calls the decision strange: "He was one of the best specialists, it will not be easy to find an equivalent replacement for him."
According to Kommersant, this will not be necessary: the post of technical director of the cosmodrome will be abolished, and its functions will be scattered among the units of TsENKI.
