Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may help ease IBD.
Red meat and chocolate are considered a nightmare for your digestive tract.
But recent research suggests the opposite: a diet rich in meat proteins and dairy products may help relieve symptoms in those who suffer from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable disease, which affects approximately 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 in the UK, leads to colic and bloating, chronic or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Usually, to relieve symptoms, patients are advised to avoid meat and dairy products, but researchers from the University of Washington found that the main amino acid of the protein tryptophan promotes the production of immune cells that increase intestinal tolerance.
Lead researcher Dr Marco Colonna explained that immune cells in the gut make sure that harmful microbes coming from food do not enter the body.
Cells that are able to trigger the inflammatory process are balanced by cells that increase tolerance, protecting the body without harming sensitive tissues.
If the balance is too much disturbed in the direction of inflammation, this can lead to inflammatory bowel diseases.
Experiments have shown that mice that have a certain bacteria in the intestines have cells that increase tolerance.
And this bacterium needs tryptophan — one of the building blocks of protein — to trigger the appearance of these cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have established a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is part of the normal gut microbiome, and the development of a population of tolerance-enhancing cells.
The more tryptophan there was in the mice’s diet, the more of these immune cells they had.”
He suggested that the same would work in humans: a combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet could contribute to a more tolerant and less inflammatory environment in the gut.
Postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragánvas, studying a variety of tolerance-enhancing immune cells, found that one group of experimental mice had these cells, and the other group, which belonged to the same line, but was contained separately, did not.
She suggested that the difference could be caused by the gut microbiomes of mice — communities of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The DNA of the mice’s gut cells was sequenced, and six types of bacteria were found present in mice that had immune cells but were absent in mice that didn’t.
Mice grown in a sterile environment that did not have a good microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cells received L. reuteri, and immune cells appeared in them.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid medium and then transferred small portions of the fluid — without the bacteria — to underdeveloped immune cells isolated from mice.
Immune cells have turned into cells that increase tolerance.
When the active ingredient was separated from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan processing, known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice’s food, the number of these cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan level was halved, the number of cells also fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that humans have the same tolerance-boosting cells as mice, and most of us have L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri contribute to cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but in people suffering from inflammatory bowel diseases, defects in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found.
She says, "We may need to step up the development of these cells, because these cells are responsible for the inflammatory processes on the inner surface of the intestines.
High levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri could potentially lead to an expansion of their population.”
