Props for the White House cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
According to military records provided to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to U.S. industrial production cost taxpayers as much as $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One" when the president is on board, became the centerpiece of a July 17 event at the White House that showcased U.S. construction programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and top White House officials inspected technology products from all fifty states.
The helicopter, made in Connecticut, was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the department responsible for helicopter control, the White House War Office ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of an “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to make sure you knew because it’s an unusual event widely covered in the press,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the first deputy chief of aviation of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive on the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 to participate in an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and would remain there until the lawn was cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required for the return flight, in line with working hours restrictions.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the event, and the unit’s security officers stayed close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
From the records obtained by TIME, it was unclear whether a second crew was needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using state property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the event contradicts this regulation.
“Among other things, we asked if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were told it wasn’t,” the commander wrote.
“You don’t seem to have anywhere to go,” the deputy chief replied.
The "Made in America" event was declared by the White House as an official event and was not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the president made efforts to advance the health care reform that was then in the Senate’s drafting, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as “Marine One” and “Air Force One” for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But to ask them only in the interests of photo-opportunity is unusual.
Trump was already the subject of discussions in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was inundated with messages complaining about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled with the Made in America show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American materials,” White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsey Walters said in a statement.
HMX-1 crews often perform training flights around the Washington agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to the White House with an accuracy of an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight performed for the Made in America event was credited to the crew for the required training flights for the month.
The unit’s helicopters also flew 11 extra hours that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks.”
According to the White House, taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A Sikorsky representative said the company did not take part in the organization of the demonstration of the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep a budget for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But, according to the Defense Department’s hourly rates for the 2017 fiscal year, the Defense Department’s reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's records show that the aircraft's time in the air was 30 minutes each way from its airfield based at Quantico Marine Corps Air Base in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using a helicopter is much lower than this rate.
“Calculating the cost to taxpayers based on an approximate reimbursement rate is completely wrong,” Walters says.
“These indicative rates include staffing, maintenance and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual appropriations.”
According to a 2015 study by RAND Corporation, reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but do account for the cost of fuel, maintenance, and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer spoke out in favor of using the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to showcase things made in America this week,” Spicer said.
And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to create.
Therefore, of course, it is quite appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was unclear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter while inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he did sit in the driver’s seat in the fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump addressed representatives of Sikorsky, joking with the press about his own fleet of products of the company.
“I know Sikorsky very well,” the president said, “I have three of them.”
